<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 15:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
RABAT -- The World Bank has extended 384 million U.S. dollars
to Morocco to finance the country's development projects and two
electric power plants.
</P>
<P>
A sizable portion of the loan will be earmarked for the
expansion of potable water networks in rural areas to serve about
1.3 million people, according to Friday's Arab daily "Al Hayat."
</P>
<P>
This is the second most important loan to be extended to
Morocco by the World Bank. Morocco obtained last month loans to
the tune of 150 million dollars for the promotion of institutional
savings and the development of the system of retirement and
pensions.
</P>
<P>
RIYADH -- The board of directors of Saudi Arabia's Arab
Petroleum Investment company has agreed to cooperate with Egyptian
banks, in extending a loan of 210 million dollars to the Egyptian
Fertilizers company to finance the construction of a chemical
fertilizers complex in the Suez Gulf industrial zone.
</P>
<P>
The loan agreement was singed on June 28 at the company head
office at the east Saudi city of Al Khobar, according to Friday's
daily "Al Hayat."
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt and Saudi Arabia have singed a contract for the
establishment of the World Steel Industries company in Egypt with
an estimated investment of 170 million dollars and a contributed
capital of 50 million dollars, Friday's Egyptian newspaper "Al
Akhbar" reported.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The Emirates Airline is going to start a fourth
line from Dubai to Dar es Salaam in July 20, less than one year
after launching the third airline to the Tanzanian capital.
</P>
<P>
The Emirates Airline operated the Dar es Salaam airline in
October 1997 and then raised the number of flights a week to two,
and to three in last March.
</P>
<P>
The Dubai-Dar es Salaam line was greatly successful as demand
on it was high for passengers and freight. 
</P>
</TEXT>
