<DOCNO> XIE19980704.0004 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Africa Should Seek Its Own Modes for Democracy: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Mozambican President Joaquim
Chissano has blasted at poverty and insecurity in Africa, saying
they have been the true obstacles to people's participation in
the democratization process in Africa.
</P>
<P>
It is very difficult for Africa to maintain a single mode for
democracy, since there are various cultures and traditions in
Africa, he told the symposium with the theme of "Africa and
Globalization: Challenges for Democracy and Governance" at its
opening ceremony here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The symposium was sponsored by the United Nations Educational,
Scientific and Cultural Organization (UNESCO).
</P>
<P>
Chissano noted at the meeting that some existing modes in
Africa are non-African, referring to the imported modes for
democracy, economic structure and development to Africa in the
second half of 1980s.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, he said, "will provide an opportunity for us to
introduce to the world our accumulated experiences over the years
in resolving peacefully the conflict, achieving national
reconciliation and respecting human rights, which would help
strengthen UNESCO's intervention ability."
</P>
<P>
Federico Mayor, director general of UNESCO, said in his speech
at the opening ceremony that the African continent should
gradually reduce its reliance on imported life mode which had
been the fragile "evil root" for most democratization process in
Africa.
</P>
<P>
"Africa should no longer be the warehouse of raw materials and
cheap labor. It should refuse any imposed mode," he added.
</P>
<P>
Mayor suggested that a best mode be designed by African
thinkers, academics, statesmen, religious experts and others, so
that a common wish for political and economic reform would be put
into practice.
</P>
<P>
The meeting scheduled to end Saturday has drawn
representatives from the Mozambican government, U.N. institutions
and others at home and abroad. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
