<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Cheif of S. African Communist Party Elected </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 3 (Xinhua) -- South African parliament member
Blade Nzimande was elected South African Communist Party (SACP)
chief Thursday at a party congress, the Star paper reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Nzimande, a parliament member of the ruling African National
Congress (ANC), was elected unopposed to succeed Charles Nqakula as
General Secretary of the SACP at the party's 10th annual congress
in Johannesburg, the report said.
</P>
<P>
This means Nzimanda will have to resign as chairman of parliament's
portfolio committee on education and give up his seat in the National
Assembly.
</P>
<P>
Nzimande's position is likely to be crucial as the SACP continues
to attempt to redefine its role within the ruling tripartite alliance
of the ANC, the SACP and the Congress of South African Trade Unions,
and in the broader political spectrum in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Nqakula was also elected unopposed as the National Chairman of the
SACP. His role, however, will be mainly ceremonial.
</P>
<P>
Welfare and Population Development Minister Geraldine
Fraser-Moleketi, who has emerged as one of the SACP's most senior
representatives in the government, was elected as deputy national
chairman.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
