<DOCNO> XIE19980704.0006 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Airways Profit Jumps </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Kenya Airways made a profit of
1.44 billion Shillings (about 24 million U.S. Dollars) before tax
in 1997, showing an increase of 32 percent over the previous
year.
</P>
<P>
A notice of the company to shareholders was quoted Friday by
the Daily Nation newspaper as saying "the results were good given
the harsh operating conditions" caused by a sharp decline in the
number of tourists visiting Kenya.
</P>
<P>
The company's net profit imporved to 1.31 billion Shillings
(more than 21.8 million U.S. Dollars) during the year, up 54
percent over 1996.
</P>
<P>
Following the improved profitability, the company paid 121.7
million Shillings (about 2.03 million U.S. Dollars) in
corporation tax last year.
</P>
<P>
The company said that the progressive development of the
airline's route network which provided convenient links between
major cities produced a 21 percent growth in business within
Africa.
</P>
<P>
"The introduction of an all jet operation has strengthened our
competitive position and our alliances with KLM (the Dutch
Airline) have produced tangible benefits both in revenues and
costs," said L.G. Kamau, a senior official with the airline.
</P>
<P>
However, he said that the company's operating costs rose by
6.7 percent in 1996, while overheads jumped to 18 percent.
</P>
<P>
The improved performance is expected to boost the company's
share price at the Nairobi Stock Exchange which was 7.20
Shillings per share Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
