<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bonn Warns against Fund-Raising for Armed Rebellion in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The German government has warned leaders
of Kosovo Albanians against using funds raised in Germany to buy
weapons for the Kosovo Liberation Army, the rebels fighting for
independence for Kosovo, the German Foreign Ministry said Friday.
</P>
<P>
According to a Foreign Ministry spokesman, the warning had been
convoyed both to Ibrahim Rugovo, a moderate Kosovo Albanian leader,
and Bujar Bukoshi, a Kosovo leader who describes himself as the prime
minister in exile and who now lives in Bonn.
</P>
<P>
The reaction from Bonn came after the special U.S. envoy, Richard
Holbrooke, said in an interview with the German newspaper Die Woche
that the Kosovo rebels were receiving funds and recruits from
supporters living in Germany, Switzerland and Denmark.
</P>
<P>
The Kosovo Liberation Army is known as the guerilla army fighting
for the independence of Kosovo on behalf of the ethnic Albanians who
make up about 90 percent of the population in the Serbian province.
</P>
<P>
Since Yugoslavia stripped Kosovo of its autonomy in 1991, more than
650,000 ethnic Albanians are said to have fled the province and about
140,000 of them have come to Germany seeking asylum.
</P>
<P>
In all, about 400,000 Kosovo Albanians now live in Germany.
</P>
<P>
The German government favor strengthened autonomy for the ethnic
Albanian majority in Kosovo, but not an independent state.
</P>
<P>
The German news agency DPA quoted government sources as saying that
there were still no concrete evidence about any "forced collection" of
funds or recruiting of ethnic Albanians living in Germany for the
Kosovo Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
The DPA also quoted an aide to Bukoshi as saying that the Kosovo
"exile government" in Bonn had been collecting a duty of three percent
of incomes from Kosovo Albanian exiles all over the world, but the
money was intended for humanitarian purposes, not for purchasing
weapons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
