<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Levy Tax on Cross-Border Goods </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 3 (Xinhua) -- South Africa is working on
fiscal measures to clamp down on commercial goods that enter
South Africa via the inefficiently controlled borders of neighbor
countries.
</P>
<P>
A 14 percent value-added tax on commercial goods from
neighboring countries into South Africa would be implemented
later this year, South African revenue service said in a
statement Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Talks to this effect are under way with South Africa's
partners in the Southern African Customs Union (SACU) - Botswana,
Lesotho, Namibia and Swaziland, South African media reported
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The measures are aimed at cracking down on the smugglers who
had avoided customs duties for years by smuggling goods into
South Africa's neighboring countries, and exporting them on to
South Africa, the revenue service said.
</P>
<P>
The tax will affect goods worth more than 10,500 Rand (1,909
Dollars), with some exemptions.
</P>
<P>
The government made the decision to tighten the borders last
year, the revenue service said.
</P>
<P>
Guidelines are being drafted ahead of the formal introduction
of the measures to ensure that they would not discourage
intra-customs union trade.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980704.0010 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India's West Bengal Shut Down by Industrial Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 3 (Xinhua) -- An industrial strike was held in
India's West Bengal state Friday in protest against the
government's economic policy and its general and railway budgets
for 1998-99.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here said the normal life in West Bengal was
disrupted by the 24-hour strike called by major trade unions.
</P>
<P>
Shops and trading centers were closed and activities in all
major industrial sectors in the state came to a standstill as
strikers picketed their respective organizations.
</P>
<P>
Buses and trams, private mini-buses and taxis were off the
roads in response to calls for the strike. Calcutta Stock Exchange
opened as usual in the morning, but later was closed due to
circumstances caused by the strike. Attendance at central
government offices and banks was thin as most trade unions
responded to the strike calls.
</P>
<P>
Train services on the eastern railway's Howrah and Sealdah
division were disrupted by strikers at different stations. Indian
Airlines' Calcutta-bound Mumbai and Delhi flights could not land
due to non-availability of meteorological briefing at the airport,
airline sources said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, opposition members in the Upper House of Parliament
Friday made a scathing attack on the government for what they
called wrong economic policies which had led to rises in prices of
essential commodities. Members of Congress, the biggest opposition
party in Parliament, said the poor have been badly hit by the
rising prices of edible oil, wheat flour, rice, fruits and
vegetables, especially the onions, in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, left party MPs Friday held a demonstration in
front of the Parliament here in protest against inflation.
</P>
</TEXT>
