<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean-U.S. Trade on Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Relations between Zimbabwe and the
United States are growing, with trade between the two countries
increasing steadily, Zimbabwe's Deputy Foreign Minister Nicholas
Goche said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Goche said trade between the two countries had been
increasing with Zimbabwe exporting goods worth more than 133 million
U.S. Dollars in 1996 while it imported goods worth 90.7 million
U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
He said this at a ceremony held here to mark the U.S. 222nd
anniversary of the declaration of independence from its former
colonial master, Britain, the Zimbabwe News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Goche said, "We have disagreed on some things and agreed on
others but that does not make us enemies."
</P>
<P>
He said the two countries had developed close working relations,
especially in the fields of politics, economic, cultural and social
spheres with the United States Aid Agency giving assistance worth
more 700 million U.S. Dollars to Zimbabwe since its independence in
1980.
</P>
<P>
"On the regional and continental levels, we welcome the U.S.
engagement with Africa particularly in the economic sphere,"
Goche said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
