<DOCNO> XIE19980704.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Sets Deadline For Gazprom's Tax </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin has
set a deadline of less than 24 hours for gas giant Gazprom to come
up with a solution to tax arrears owed to the state.
</P>
<P>
The president made the demand in talks Friday with Rem
Vyakhirev, chief of the partially state-owned Gazprom, the world's
biggest gas producer, presidential spokesman Sergei Yastrzhembsky
said.
</P>
<P>
But the spokesman said solutions essential for both Gazprom and
the Russian economy had come out of the meeting.
</P>
<P>
A "steady system for checking debts and conducting offset
payments" would be worked out to allow Gazprom to pay its taxes,
and get paid by customers whose arrears to Gazprom had piled up
its debt, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The two sides had a "fairly stiff talk" about the situation
over the gas company. Gazprom was warned by the government on
Thursday to pay its tax debt or face seizure of property, he said.
</P>
<P>
The gas company was blamed for defaulting on current tax
payments to the federal budget. According to Deputy Prime Minister
Oleg Sysuyev, Gazprom has paid only a third of its tax dues by
June.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin stressed at the meeting that it is necessary for all to
fully pay taxes, no matter whether it is a big or small enterprise
or a monopoly, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
On a related development, Prime Minister Sergei Kiriyenko
insisted that everybody in Russia should pay taxes, including
Gazprom.
</P>
<P>
"The government is interested in one thing only -- tax
payments." He warned about the imposition of forced measures in
tax collection.
</P>
<P>
Moscow has begun putting pressure on companies in tax arrears
to pay up. The action is part of a government austerity package
aimed at avoiding financial collapse. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
