<HEADLINE> Gazprom Considers Canceling Trust Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Russian gas giant Gazprom is
considering an annulment of its trust contract with the Russian
government, Gazprom chief Rem Vyakhirev said Friday.
</P>
<P>
After separate talks Friday with President Boris Yeltsin and
Prime Minister Sergei Kiriyenko, Vyakhirev said: "Probably on
Tuesday, we most likely will make the decision to break the trust
contract."
</P>
<P>
The contract for trust management of the government's 35
percent stake in Gazprom was signed by Vyakhirev and Kiriyenko,
then fuel and energy minister, in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The Russian Prime Minister on Thursday ordered the abolition of
the trust agreement with Gazprom because of its shortfall in tax
payments, and it was intended to convene an extraordinary meeting
of Gazprom shareholders.
</P>
<P>
But Vyakhirev said an accord had been made on a new tax debt
repayment scheme to work from July 1, under which Gazprom
undertook to pay all the tax owed to the federal budget on the
condition that enterprises pay their debts to the company for gas
deliveries.
</P>
<P>
A commission was set up to prepare a draft document on
settlements between Gazprom and the government, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
