<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 16:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon Arrests Suspects of Bombings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese military intelligence has
arrested 11 of a 20-man terrorist ring that has engineered a
series of bomb explosions in the past two years, including the
recent grenade blast near the U.S. Embassy in Beirut.
</P>
<P>
The National Broadcast Network radio quoted a military source
as saying that nine of the ring are still at large.
</P>
<P>
Most of the ring are ex-members of the outlawed Lebanese
Forces (LF) and are controlled by the central LF bureau in
Australia "possibly with direct support and guidance from
Israel's intelligence apparatuses."
</P>
<P>
The LF was the Christians' main militia during Lebanon's
1975-1990 sectarian civil war and has been opposed to Syrian
military presence in Lebanon. Syria has been deploying a 40,000
forces in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Its leader Maronite Christian Samir Geagea, is currently on
trial for the 1987 assassination of Sunni Muslim Prime Minister
Rashid Karami.
</P>
<P>
The 11 detainees have confessed that they staged a gunfire
attack that killed a Syrian driver in northern Beirut on December
12, 1996 and bombed the newly-opened public transport station used
by Lebanese and Syrian transportation services near the Beirut
port on October 28, 1997.
</P>
<P>
They also confessed to frequent bombing attacks on the offices
of the National Syrian Socialist Party across the country in the
past three months.
</P>
<P>
The ring also said that they had sent faxes to banking and
trading firms calling for an armed uprising.
</P>
<P>
A communique distributed by Lebanese intelligence said the
clue that led to the discovery of the ring was the June 19 car
bomb blast in Beirut's low-income residential neighborhood of Dora.
</P>
<P>
The two men killed by an explosive charge they were carrying in
the car belonged to the "shock troops" of the LF.
</P>
<P>
The communique said all the 11 detainees have been turned over
to judicial authorities along with their written confessions and
explosives, detonators, timers and maps seized.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, security branches are following up the link between
the ring and another bomb explosion which took place at the campus
of the American University in Beirut last year, the communique
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980704.0023 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lesotho Announces Budget Deficit for 1998/99 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Lesotho's budget for the
1998/99 financial year provides for total revenues and grants of
2.37 billion Maloti (395 million U.S. Dollars), Lesotho's Finance
and Development Planning Minister Leketekete Ketso said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Budgeted expenditures for the year totals 2.81 billion Maloti
(468 million Dollars), Ketso said in his budget speech in the
National Assembly.
</P>
<P>
This represented a 435.8 million Maloti (73 million Dollars)
deficit, South African media reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The bulk of Lesotho's revenue will continue to be derived from
its share of the receipts from the Southern African Customs Union
(SACU), which includes South Africa, Botswana, Namibia and
Swaziland.
</P>
<P>
Lesotho's customs revenue totals 1,033.4 million Maloti (172
million Dollars) or 46 percent of total revenue for the 1998/99
financial year, according to the budget.  
</P>
</TEXT>
