<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rwandan Govt Committed to Pay $100M to Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The Rwandan government has
expressed its commitment to clearing a debt amounting to 30
the workers, the Rwanda News Agency (RNA) said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Rwandan Minister of Labor and Public Service Nsengimana Joseph
made the pledge Thursday at the close of a two-day national
conference on "Structural Adjustment Program (SAP) and its social
dimension" organized by local Trade Unions in Kigali.
</P>
<P>
The minister assured the workers in the country on the
government initiative of paying what it owes to their National
Social Security Fund.
</P>
<P>
Joseph said that the government will pay "this debt in
installments of eight million Rwanda Francs each year from 1998."
</P>
<P>
The debt is just a part of the heap of internal debts ranging
from 85 to 100 billion Rwanda Francs accumulated by the preceding
government from private and public creditors, said RNA.
</P>
<P>
At the conference organized by the Confederation of Rwandan
Trade Unions CESTRAR with the support of the International
Confederation of Free Trade Unions African Regional Organization
(ICFTU-AFRO), the representatives of unions fiercely attacked
government for endorsing the three-year structural economic
reform program without consulting workers organizations who are
the victims of the reform measures.
</P>
<P>
In April this year, the Rwandan government put out a
three-year Economic Reform Program, ESAF (Enhanced Structural
Adjustment Facility), for 1998-2001.
</P>
<P>
The program, sponsored by the International Monetary Fund and
the World Bank, involves privatization of public enterprises,
public service reform, fiscal reform and the creation of
competitive economy.
</P>
<P>
"The workers are the victims of retrenchment, privatization,
budget cut on social expenditure. Then why shouldn't we be
consulted?" questioned Murangira (RNA did not give his full name)
the Secretary-General of the CESTRAR at the conference.
</P>
<P>
"We are not against SAP but the social partners must be
consulted,"insisted Andrew Kaleimbo, the General-Secretary of
ICFTU-AFRO, who attended the meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
