<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethio-Djibouti Rail Transports 39,000 Tons of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The Ethio-Djibouti Railway
Company announced Friday that it has ferried 39,000 tons of goods
from Port Djibouti into the hinterland in just a month.
</P>
<P>
The company is giving a round-the-clock service since Ethiopia
began to use the Djibouti port as its sole outlet, the manager of
its Dire Dawa Branch, Girma Birru, told local press.
</P>
<P>
The manager said that 10,000 tons of fertilizers, 19,000 tons
of merchandise and 6,000 tons of grains and raw materials have
been transported into the hinterland.
</P>
<P>
According to the manager, the company used to transport over
three hundred tons of goods daily and the company transported
fuel and fuel products only to eastern Ethiopia in the earlier
days.
</P>
<P>
Every day, 300 tons of fuel is being transported to Ethiopia,
said Birru.
</P>
<P>
After the outbreak of Ethio-Eritrean border dispute on May 6
this year, Ethiopia has diverted from Assab Port of Eritrea to
Port Djibouti as its outlet.
</P>
<P>
Seventy percent of Ethiopia's exports and imports used to
transit through Assab, which was one of Ethiopia's two seaports
before the independence of Eritrea in May, 1993.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, about 300 freight trucks are moving a total of
6,000 tons a day by road through Djibouti, according to an
earlier announcement by the Ethiopian government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
