<DOCNO> XIE19980704.0044 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> People's Daily Hails Clinton's China Visit (Part One) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Beijing, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The People's Daily, in a commentary
to be published on Saturday, hails the achievements of the just
concluded China visit by U.S. President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
At the invitation of Chinese President Jiang Zemin, Clinton
visited China from June 25 to July 3, another important event in
the Sino-U.S. relations following President Jiang's state visit to
the United States last year, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
During his nine-day stay in China, Clinton toured Xi'an,
Beijing, Shanghai, Guilin and the Special Administrative Region of
Hong Kong, and held a summit meeting with President Jiang.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders exchanged views thoroughly on bilateral
relations as well as major international and regional issues and
shared extensive and important common views.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing summit is conducive to widening their mutual
understanding, promoting friendship, expanding common ground and
developing cooperation. Thus it is a firm step forward to building
a constructive strategic partnership between the two countries
oriented toward the 21st century, the paper noted.
</P>
<P>
The summit is positive, constructive and fruitful, the paper
said.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders conducted fruitful consultation on major
international issues. Their agreement on de-targeting each other
with their strategic nuclear weapons demonstrates to the world
that China and the United States are cooperative partners, not
rivals.
</P>
<P>
They also achieved positive outcomes on the issues of keeping
stability in the Asian region, curbing nuclear arms race in South
Asia, maintaining peace and stability in the Korea peninsula,
preventing nuclear proliferation and fighting against
international crime, drug trafficking and terrorism.
</P>
<P>
The two nations issued three joint statements on South Asia,
the inspection protocol to the Biological Weapons Convention and
the issue of anti-personnel mines respectively.
</P>
<P>
In discussing the Asian financial crisis, the United States
spoke highly of the vital role China played in helping easing it,
the paper said.
</P>
<P>
The two sides agreed to further strengthen their strategic
dialogue in economy and finance to make contributions to the
development of world economy and international finance, the paper
said.
</P>
<P>
The summit injected new vigor into the Sino-U.S. economic and
trade cooperation. American businessmen with President Clinton on
the visit showed great interest in strengthening economic and
trade relations with China.
</P>
<P>
Before and after the visit, companies and institutions from
both sides signed 12 key cooperation contracts worth about three
billion U.S. dollars in U.S. favor.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the two governments signed an agreement on peaceful
use of nuclear technology, and decided to strengthen their
exchange and cooperation in environmental protection, science,
education and legal matters.
</P>
<P>
The Taiwan issue was an important topic during the
summit. President Jiang stressed that this issue is the most
important and sensitive core issue in Sino-U.S. relations.
</P>
<P>
Clinton publicly reiterated that the United States upholds the
one-China policy and abides by the principles contained in the
three Sino-U.S. joint communiques, and does not support Taiwan's
independence, nor "one China, one Taiwan", nor "two Chinas," nor
Taiwan's bid to join any international organizations made of only
sovereign states.
</P>
<P>
To deepen mutual understanding is a precondition for the
development of the Sino-U.S. relationship. Only when they
understand each other can the two countries increase their mutual
trust and cooperation, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
During the tour, Clinton not only reviewed China's glorious
history and culture of 5,000 years but also saw a vigorous modern
China.
</P>
<P>
By meeting Chinese people, President Clinton saw for himself
the great achievements China has made since it opened up to the
outside world and the high spirit the Chinese people have
displayed in building a stronger and more prosperous China, and
felt the friendly feelings they have for the American people.
</P>
<P>
Seeing is believing. President Clinton expressed belief that
his China tour deepened his understanding of China's history and
reality and helped the American people gain a complete picture of
China.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980704.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> People's Daily Hails Clinton's China Visit (Part Two) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
He said that a more prosperous, open and stronger new China is
emerging in the world.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese and American leaders shook hands once again across
the Pacific and won worldwide appreciation. World media all hailed
the outcome of the summit.
</P>
<P>
The New York Times noted that U.S. and Chinese leaders share
broad agreement in building a partnership while the Washington
Post holds that the Sino-U.S. relations will turn a new page to
the welcome of most Americans.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese newspaper Asahi Shimbun commented that exchange of
visits by Chinese and American leaders demonstrate that the two
countries have gone from an era of confrontation to that of
cooperation, which is beneficial to Asia's stability and world
peace at large.
</P>
<P>
Thai statesmen said that Clinton's visit to China has sent a
positive message to the world: the role China can play in regional
and global affairs should not be underestimated.
</P>
<P>
Reports said most Americans support Clinton's China trip and
praise the Sino-U.S. summit, proving that opposition to Clinton's
visit is short-sighted and unpopular.
</P>
<P>
In short, to improve and develop Sino-U.S. relations conforms
to the trend of the times and cannot be hampered by any force.
</P>
<P>
While reaching broad agreement on international and bilateral
issues, China and the United States did not sidestep their
differences over human rights. It is not strange that the two
sides have differences over some issues, the important point is
that these differences should not stand in the way of the
development of bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
World opinion believes that the frank exchange of views between
Jiang and Clinton shows that the Sino-U.S. relations are growing
mature.
</P>
<P>
China has always maintained that differences between countries
should be reduced through equal consultation and dialogue in the
spirit of mutual respect and seeking common ground while reserving
differences.
</P>
<P>
Any practice of interfering in the internal affairs of other
countries and imposing one's view on others does not help solve
any problem.
</P>
<P>
The Sino-U.S. relations will undoubtedly further develop as
long as the two countries continue to examine and handle them from
a strategic height and a long-term view.
</P>
<P>
The improvement of Sino-U.S. relations is a historical
necessity, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
President Jiang has pointed out that under the new historical
conditions, China and the United States share extensive common
interest and shoulder unshirkable common responsibilities when
dealing with the major issues concerning peace and development of
the Asia-Pacific region and the whole world.
</P>
<P>
President Clinton holds that the trend of the development of
Sino-U.S. relations will decide to a large extent whether the new
century is a safe, peaceful and prosperous century for the
American people.
</P>
<P>
The achievements of the Beijing summit shows that the
development of friendship and cooperation between the two
countries, as U.N. Security Council permanent members with global
significance, conforms to the fundamental interest of the Chinese
and American peoples and contributes to world peace and
development as well, the paper concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
