<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senventeen S. Leonean Soldiers Face Court-Martial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Some 17 soldiers of the disbanded
Sierra Leonean army will face a court-martial next week to answer
charges of treason, which is a capital offense, according to a
report reaching here Friday.
</P>
<P>
The soldiers, if found guilty of the allegations in connection
with the junta ousted last mid-February, could be shot, it said.
</P>
<P>
Among them is Corporal Tamba Gborie, who went on the National
Radio on May 25, 1997 to announce that the army had seized power
from elected President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
They also include Commander Victor King, who headed the air
force.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the judgement of the court-martial is
final and not subject to any appeal.
</P>
<P>
A legal official was quoted as saying "only the presidential
committee for the prerogative of mercy will meet after the
judgement to confirm or reduce the sentences passed by the
court-martial."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, some 59 civilians are also on trial for treason for
their alleged involvement with the junta, which was reousted from
the capital Freetown by the west African peacekeeping force
ECOMOG last February. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
