<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda Leaves Media to Fend for Itself </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The Ugandan government has allowed
the media department to use its revenue to run its operations,
the first time ever in the country's history, a senior official
said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Minister of State for Information in the President's office
Basoga Nsadhu told Radio Uganda that the revenue collection in
the department has been computerized for effective management and
to minimize embezzlement.
</P>
<P>
When addressing Radio Uganda staff at Broadcasting house here,
the minister warned that anyone who is found embezzling Radio
Uganda and Uganda Television commercial revenue will have their
services terminated without delay.
</P>
<P>
A new format of advertisement and sponsored programs that
responds to the department's new challenges will be instituted.
</P>
<P>
He described his new mission in the department as ensuring the
establishment of three new viable agencies: Uganda News Agency
which is to handle domestic and international news, School of
Media and Graphic Arts and Uganda Broadcasting Agency or
Corporation.
</P>
<P>
On the occasion, the minister also expressed his
disappointment at the failure of the relevant organs to implement
the press and journalists statute and that of the electronic
media, which were initiated three years ago.
</P>
<P>
In an earlier government reshuffle, the Ministry of
Information which had been responsible for the management of
media organizations in the country was purged and a media
department in the President's office has taken over the
ministry's functions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
