<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading British Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items in
leading British newspapers Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Times:
</P>
<P>
-- Tony Blair flew into Northern Ireland Thursday night on a
high-risk mission to avert a looming confrontation that could yet
destroy the Province's fragile peace. As he left at midnight
officials said only that he had managed to "open up dialogue".
</P>
<P>
Financial Times:
</P>
<P>
-- The European Central Bank has announced that there would be no
minimum thresholds for trasactions under the Target system, the
cross-border payments network for the euro-zone.
</P>
<P>
The Daily Telegraph:
</P>
<P>
-- Two new aircraft carriers, a single battlefield helicopter
force and a streamlined support structure allowing the army to
deploy at division strength to two troublespots simultaneously are
among the main points of British government's Strategic Defence
Review to be published next week.
</P>
<P>
The Independent:
</P>
<P>
