<HEADLINE> S. African Banks Raise Interest Rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 3 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's three major
banks Friday hiked their prime lending rates and mortgage rates
again after the Rand fell to a new low against the U.S. Dollar
and the British Pound.
</P>
<P>
The increases are the highest real interest hike in the
history of the country, SABC, the South African national
television reported.
</P>
<P>
Standard Bank announced that it will raise its primary lending
rate by one percentage point to 23.25 percent and its mortgage
rate from 20 to 22 percent.
</P>
<P>
Nedcor followed suit by raising its benchmark rate to 24
percent and its home loan rate to 21.50 percent.
</P>
<P>
ABSA also increased its prime rate to 23.75 percent and its
mortgage rate to 21.50 percent.
</P>
<P>
An economist predicts that the interest rates could be lower
in about one or two months' time, but they will not be back at 18
percent, the level before the crisis began in late May.
</P>
<P>
The Rand Friday slipped to 6.43 against the U.S. Dollar and
10.63 against the British Pound.
</P>
<P>
Since the crisis began, the banks had raised their rates three
times from 18.25 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Reserve Bank's tightening of monetary policy to defend the
Rand has not stopped the speculative attack, which inflicted
losses of more than 23 percent of its value against the U.S.
Dollar. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
