<HEADLINE> Iran Claims Former IRGC Commander's Son Kidnapped </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Iran Friday rejected the claim that
Ahmad Rezaee, son of former commander of the Islamic Revolutionary
Guards Corps (IRGC) Mohsen Rezaee sought asylum in the United
States, but saying that he was kidnapped by Americans.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Iranian official news agency IRNA,
Ahmad's brother Ali Rezaee said that Ahmad was kidnapped by the
U.S. National Aeronautical and Space Administration (NASA)
"through a perfect plot initiated by an agent Majid Tawana one
year ago."
</P>
<P>
The interview was carried out after the Voice of America (VOA)
Persian program broadcast an interview with Ahmad in Los Angeles
Thursday night who said he has sought asylum in the U.S..
</P>
<P>
Ali said that his 21-year-old brother phoned home in tears on
Friday and told them that "he had been threatened to give an
interview with VOA on Iranian supreme leader" Ayatollah Ali
Khamenei.
</P>
<P>
He said Tawana had persuaded his father Mohsen Rezaee to go
with him to the U.S., but the plot was neutralized by his father,
who is current secretary of the country's State Expediency
Council, a powerful advisory body to Khamenei.
</P>
<P>
In relation to this plot, the U.S. government and State
Department had issued an official visa for Mohsen Rezaee to
inspect an incomplete military installation in the U.S., Ali said.
</P>
<P>
He said that Ahmad, a sophomore studying pure mathematics at
Tehran's Teacher Training University, paid a visit to United Arab
Emirates last year where he was offered a job, but he soon
realized that it was a trap set by the Iranian outlawed Mujahedin
Khalq Organization (MKO).
</P>
<P>
Once he became aware of the MKO plot, he decided to return
home, Ali said, however before he could materialize his plan, he
was kidnapped en route.
</P>
<P>
In order to make the whole kidnapping scene look natural,
Ahmad was taken to several European countries and in last March he
was transferred to the U.S., he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
