<HEADLINE> Ugandan Army Planning to Incorporate Geneva </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Uganda People's Defense Forces
(UPDF) has plans to incorporate the law of armed conflict as
spelt out in the internationally-recognized Geneva convention,
according to military officials.
</P>
<P>
Director of Military Intelligence Colonel Henry Tumukunde made
the statement when closing a one-day seminar on the law of war
here Friday afternoon, Radio Uganda reported.
</P>
<P>
This law of armed conflict is a set of rules enshrined in the
general convention that prohibits soldiers at the battle field
from killing indiscriminately and orders them to render humane
treatment to civilians and enemies who are not armed.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening of the seminar, the UPDF Chief
Political Commissar Lt. Colonel Robert Rusoke attributed the
army's many victories to its respect for the law of armed
conflict.
</P>
<P>
It has become very crucial for the UPDF to master and observe
the law of war since the force has been earmarked for
international peacekeeping missions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
