<HEADLINE> Trial of Suspects in Rwanda Genocide Adjourned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The International Criminal
Tribunal for Rwanda (ICTR) has announced that the joint trial of
two suspects has been adjourned to next month when more defense
witnesses are expected to continue giving evidence.
</P>
<P>
Trial of the suspects, Clement Kayishema, a former Prefect of
Rwanda's Kibuye, and a former businessman Obed Ruzindana, will
resume on August 17, according to a press release Friday by ICTR
based in north Tanzania's Arusha town.
</P>
<P>
The trial has been adjourned at the request of the defendant,
who told the court that the accused have "15 more very important
witnesses who are presently said to be scattered in various
refugee camps and other locations out of Rwanda."
</P>
<P>
In this regard, the statement said, the Witnesses and Victims
Protection Unit Thursday requested the Chamber 2 to give it
adequate time to bring them before the tribunal.
</P>
<P>
The last defense witness was Dr. Regis Pouget, a psychiatrist
who finished testifying on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Fifty-two prosecution witnesses and 17 defense witnesses have
already testified in the trial which began on April 7, 1997.
</P>
<P>
Kayishema and Ruzindana are jointly charged with genocide,
crimes against humanity, violations of Article 3 Common to the
Geneva Conventions and of Additional Protocol 2.
</P>
<P>
They have pleaded "not guilty" to six joint counts, while
Kayishema is separately charged with 18 other counts.
</P>
<P>
The court was established by the United Nations to try chief
suspects of Rwanda's 1994 genocide. Over 800,000 Tutsis and
moderate Hutus were killed by Hutu extremists in a three-month
slaughter that ended with the Tutsi-dominated Rwanda Patriotic
Front seizing power. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
