<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia to Retain Nuclear Forces Till 2010 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Russia will retain its strategic
nuclear triad of ground, sea and air forces until the year 2010,
Russia's Security Council announced Friday.
</P>
<P>
According to the Interfax news agency, the decision was taken
by the Security Council at a regular session chaired by President
Boris Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
At the session, concrete decisions on the structure and
strength of Russia's nuclear forces were adopted.
</P>
<P>
It wad said that ground troops are to be equipped with one type
of Topol-M intercontinental ballistic missiles in stationary and
mobile modifications, instead of the six types of missiles used
today.
</P>
<P>
The first stationary complexes of this system were brought
online last year. The Topol-M system is expected to stay active at
least until the year 2020.
</P>
<P>
The participants of the session agreed to boost naval nuclear
potential. The main efforts are to be applied in the near future
toward maintaining the military preparedness of Delta-IV
nuclear-powered submarine cruisers that carry missiles and to a
number of other forces.
</P>
<P>
It was also decided to reduce nuclear potential in the air
force and upgrade Tu-95 and Tu-160 bombers with long-range
missiles. These aircraft, the first of which was designed back in
the 1950s, will remain in service at least until 2015 just like
B-52 and B-1 bombers.
</P>
<P>
The council's press service said that the president instructed
the council and cabinet to pay as much attention as possible to
the problems of scientific organizations and industrial
enterprises involved in space, missile and nuclear weapons
programs.
</P>
<P>
At the session, funds for corresponding programs were earmarked
and decisions on economic, scientific and industrial measures to
ensure nuclear deterrence were adopted, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
