<HEADLINE> Turkey Vows to Prevent Deployment of Russian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Deputy Prime Minister
Bulent Ecevit reaffirmed Saturday that Turkey is determined to
prevent Cyprus' plan to deploy Russian-made S-300 missiles on the
divided island.
</P>
<P>
Ecevit made the remark at a press conference held on the
occasion of the 1st anniversary of the 55th Turkish government.
</P>
<P>
"We are carefully monitoring the excessive armament policy
adopted by the Southern Cyprus Greek Administration with the
support of Greece. This excessive armament drive has found its
way into the purchase of Russian S-300 missiles," Ecevit said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Turkish government was adopting the required
military countermeasures against the probability of their actual
commitment.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into Greek Cypriot-dominated south and
Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since 1974 when Turkish troops
landed and took over the northern third of the island in response
to a pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
Early last year, Cyprus signed an accord with Russia to buy the
S-300 missiles, triggering tensions on the small island. Turkey
has vowed to use all means to block the deployment of the missiles.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has rescheduled the deployment of the missiles from
mid-year to October or November. Russia has turned down the
pressure from some countries and said it will go ahead with the
deal.
</P>
<P>
Ecevit added that "I want to reiterate here that all actions to
be launched by the Southern Cyprus Greek Administration and Greece
under their so-called joint defense doctrine have been and will be
countered with due determination."
</P>
<P>
Turkey has been provided political, economic and military
support to Turkish Cypriots and is the sole country to recognize
the "Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus" unilaterally declared by
Turkish Cypriots in 1983.
</P>
<P>
At present, more than 35,000 Turkish government troops are
stationed in northern Cyprus with a claimed aim to protect Turkish
Cypriots. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
