<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Foreign Accounts Restrictions Would Be Eased </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Finance Minister Sartaj
Aziz hopes restrictions imposed on foreign currency accounts would
be eased within the next three to four months provided economic
conditions improve, exports increase and the foreign exchange
situation stabilizes.
</P>
<P>
In a meeting at the Karachi Chamber of Commerce and Industry on
Saturday, Aziz said the government has already relaxed the foreign
currency accounts and new deposits could now be withdrawn.
</P>
<P>
"We have maintained certain immunity on the foreign currency
accounts while facilities of duty exemptions are also available to
the same accounts," he was quoted by the Associated Press of
Pakistan as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said the government maintained accounts in foreign currency
to attract foreign investment. Only 1.2 billion U.S. dollars out
of 10 billion dollar deposits belonged to the non-resident
Pakistanis, whereas the rest of the deposits in foreign currency
were maintained by accounts from local residents.
</P>
<P>
He said the existence of foreign currency accounts had become a
source of investment, not savings, as people were fast converting
their rupee deposits into dollars besides putting their export
earnings into foreign currency accounts.
</P>
<P>
The decision to freeze foreign currency accounts after
Pakistan's nuclear tests at the end of May was taken in the wake
of uncontrolled withdrawals from these accounts during a period
between May 11 and 28, when 52 million dollars were withdrawn in a
single day, according to Aziz.
</P>
<P>
He said the government had no other way but to freeze the
foreign currency accounts.
</P>
<P>
The minister also said Pakistan is passing through a difficult
time and the next three to four months were crucial.
</P>
<P>
Aziz hinted that the situation would largely depend on whether
international institutions will release or withhold loans to
Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that the International Monetary Fund, the World Bank
and the Asian Development Bank, being independent institutions and
having their separate charters, would not come into the influence
of a single country," he said, adding that if they impose
sanctions on Pakistan, it will damage the independent image of
these institutions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980704.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia's Currency Depreciation May Ignite </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 4 (Xinhua) -- The Civil Servants Union of Zambia
(CSUZ) said Saturday that the continued depreciation of the
country's currency is eroding the real income of most employees
and could led to widespread strikes.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Zambia News Agency, CSUZ General
Secretary Japhet Moonde said the depreciation of the Kwacha is
pushing the prices of commodities beyond the reach of many
people.
</P>
<P>
The economic condition prevailing in the country are too harsh
for most of the workers to cope with unless their salaries are
increased, said the union leader.
</P>
<P>
He noted that a lot of workers are being demoralized because
of the low wages they are receiving and productivity is going
down as a result.
</P>
<P>
Moonde warned that if workers are pushed too hard against the
wall of poverty it could breed widespread strikes as workers
press for better salaries and other conditions of service to
survive.
</P>
<P>
He accused employers including the government for being
insensitive to the plight of workers, adding that there is need
to resolve the root causes of industrial strife instead of taking
a confrontational stand.
</P>
<P>
As far as the two-week go-slow by magistrates starting last
week for increased wages and better conditions of service, Moonde
said the government should move quickly to dialog with the
magistrates countrywide.
</P>
<P>
In the past 10 months, the Kwacha has depreciated by nearly 40
percent, falling from 1,330 to the Dollar last September to over
1,950 against one U.S. Dollar at present.
</P>
<P>
The Zambian government began to implement a wage freeze
program against civil servants last year, which has deteriorated
the living conditions of the country's civil servants and
industrial workers. The matter has already been taken to court.
</P>
</TEXT>
