<DOCNO> XIE19980704.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Records Big Trade Surplus for January-May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia registered a hefty
trade surplus in the first five months of this year due to a
stronger growth in exports, the Statistics Department said
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The surplus amounted to 16.2 billion ringgit (3.95 billion U.S.
dollars) against the mere 48.5 million ringgit (11.829 million
dollars) during the same period last year, the department said.
</P>
<P>
The cumulative exports and imports for the January-May period
amounted to 115 billion ringgit (28.05 billion dollars) and 98.8
billion ringgit (24.097 billion dollars) respectively.
</P>
<P>
Exports during January-May grew sharply by 40.5 percent or 33.2
billion ringgit (8.1 billion dollars) compared with the previous
corresponding period, while imports rose 20.8 percent or 17
billion ringgit (4.15 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
The department said if imports and re-exports of "lumpy" items
(namely aircraft and ships/tankers, including accessories) were to
be excluded, the country would have been registering a larger
surplus of 19.2 billion ringgit (4.68 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
In the first five months of the year, electrical and electronic
products remained as the largest export earners, with total
earnings of 59.3 billion ringgit (14.46 billion dollars) or 51.6
percent of the country's total export revenue.
</P>
<P>
Palm oil, with a value of 6.5 billion ringgit (1.59 billion
dollars), constituted 5.7 percent of exports and remained the
second largest revenue earner.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, imports of intermediate goods rose 26.7 percent to
68.3 billion ringgit (16.66 billion dollars), while capital goods
grew 8.3 percent to 17.2 billion ringgit (4.2 billion dollars) and
consumer goods expanded 6.3 percent to 5.5 billion ringgit (1.34
billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
The United States, Japan and Singapore continued to be
Malaysia's major trading partners, accounting for 51.7 percent of
Malaysia's total trade during the first five months of the year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
