<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Water Levels Exceed Warning Line On Major Rivers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 4 (Xinhua) -- The water levels on China's major
rivers -- including the Yangtze, Huaihe and Nenjiang rivers --
have risen above warning lines, according to a report issued today
by the National headquarters for Control of Floods and Droughts.
</P>
<P>
The report, the fifth of the year, states that the flood's peak
on the main stream of the Yangtze River, the largest in China, has
passed Shashi City in central Chinas Hubei Province, while the
water level at 8 a.m. today at the Jianli Measuring Station was
0.01 higher than the previous record high.
</P>
<P>
In southern Guangdong Province, more than 2,000 soldiers
reportedly succeeded in blocking a breached dike on a tributary of
the Beijiang River this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Local officials will start an investigation into the breached
dike which was built at the end of last year, according to
Deputy-Governor Ou Guangyuan. The official said he had doubts
about the quality of the dike. 
</P>
</TEXT>
