<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 14:30 GMT, July 4 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO -- Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto on Saturday
hailed United States President Bill Clinton's just concluded state
visit to China as a great success.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto made the remark during a meeting at his official
residence in Tokyo with U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright, who arrived here Friday night from Hong Kong to brief
Japan on Clinton's visit to China.
</P>
<P>
The bulk of their 25-minute meeting was spent discussing
Clinton's China visit, Japanese government officials said.
(Japan-U.S.-Albright)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BELGRADE -- Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic Friday called
on the international community to stop pressuring and threatening
his country on the Kosovo issue.
</P>
<P>
The terrorist activities by the ethnic Albanians in Kosovo must
also be stopped, said Milosevic while meeting with a
U.S. delegation headed by Richard Holbrooke, U.S. ambassador to
the Uninted Nations.
</P>
<P>
Milosevic stressed that talks between the representatives from
the Yugoslav Serb government and ethnic Albanians in Kosovo must
continue, as the political means is the only peaceful solution to
the issue. (Yugoslavia-Kosovo-Call)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TIRANA -- The Macedonian troops in the border areas with
Albania and Yugoslavia have been placed in a state of alert due to
the deteriorating situation in Kosovo, reports from the Macedonian
capital of Skoplje said.
</P>
<P>
Announcing the decision Thursday, President Kiro Gligorov
reaffirmed that his country opposes any attempt to change a
country's borders by force and supports a peaceful solution to the
Kosovo issue through dialogue.
</P>
<P>
It is the first time that Macedonia has declared a state of
alert since armed conflicts broke out in Kosovo last February.
(Macedonia-Kosovo-Alert)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ALMA-ATA -- Visiting Chinese President Jiang Zemin and his
Kazakh counterpart Nursultan Nazarbayev signed a supplementary
agreement on border issues between the two countries on Saturday
morning.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese president said the signing of the accord, the
second of its kind, marks a complete resolution to their remaining
border issues.
</P>
<P>
China and Kazakhstan signed a border agreement in April, 1994
and their first supplementary border agreement was signed during
Jiang's official visit to Kazakhstan in July, 1996.
(Kazakhstan-China-Border Agreement) 
</P>
