<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-04 14:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish Prime Minister Vows to Fight High Inflation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz
said on Saturday that his government will make greater efforts to
bring down the soaring inflation rate.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference on the occasion of the
anniversary of the 55th Turkish government, Yilmaz said that to
curb the high inflation rate is one of the most important tasks of
his government.
</P>
<P>
"Many of the problems and imbalances experienced in this
country are underlain by the high inflation rate which we have not
been able to overcome in the last 30 years," Yilmaz said.
</P>
<P>
"Fight against the inflation is a multidimensional task,
requiring first of all an absolute political determination and a
serious political sacrifice. It requires a realistic program
coupled with social support and comprehension," he added.
</P>
<P>
Turkey's inflation rate, which stood at 80 percent at the end
of June, and the severe devaluation of the currency Turkish Lira
have become a major bottleneck for its economic development.
</P>
<P>
Yilmaz said the Turkish government intends to cut the inflation
rate down to 50 percent at the end of this year and 20 percent in
1999.
</P>
<P>
"Our successfully-pursued program for abating the inflation is
being monitored with much appreciation by world's leading finance
and economy organizations," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish prime minister stressed that his government would
firmly push ahead with privatization plan as part of the efforts
to revitalize the economy.
</P>
<P>
The present government came to power in July last year when
former Prime Minister Necmettin Erbakan was forced to resign due
to pro-Islamic tendency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
