<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Students Take Education Ministry to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Students of Harare Polytechnic
College have filed an urgent application in the high court,
seeking an order for the Ministry of Higher Education to reopen
the college which was closed after disturbances last month at the
instiution.
</P>
<P>
Lawyer of the students, Tinomudaishe Chinyoka Saturday
confirmed that he had filed the application and expected the case
to be heard Monday, the Zimbabwe News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
President of the Student Representative Council, Charlton
Hwende said they made the application on Friday citing the
ministry as the respondent.
</P>
<P>
Hwende said they had resorted to legal action because nothing
was being done to discuss the plight of the college whereas the
authorities at the University of Zimbabwe were trying to seek a
solution on the closure of the institution.
</P>
<P>
''The ministry has been silent about the Harare Polytechnic
College issue and that is why we have taken this course of
action,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
Harare Polytechnic College and the University of Zimbabwe were
closed indefinitely last month following violent demonstrations
by students who were demanding an increase in their payouts.
</P>
