<HEADLINE> 2ndlead: Quake Hits Southeastern Turkey Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 4 (Xinhua) -- An earthquake measuring 4.4
degrees on the open-ended Richter scale hit southeastern Turkey
Saturday afternoon. There was no immediate report of casualties.
</P>
<P>
The quake took place at 12:25 local time (09:25 GMT) and its
epicenter was located at the city of Ceyhan, 40 kilometers east of
Adana which was stricken by a 5.1-degree earthquake early
Saturday, the Anatolia News Agency said.
</P>
<P>
More than 400 people were reportedly injured in the shake in
Adana.
</P>
<P>
Reports said some people were injured after jumping from their
balconies and some others suffered heart attack in great panic.
</P>
<P>
The injured have been rushed to hospitals.
</P>
<P>
The quake in Adana is the strongest of more than 70 aftershocks
after the previous tremor a week ago, measuring 6.3 degrees and
killing 140 people and injuring more than 1,500 others.
</P>
<P>
Many displaced residents live in their makeshift tents for
fear of more aftershocks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
