<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese PM Calls Clinton's China Tour Great Success </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto on Saturday hailed United States President Bill
Clinton's just concluded state visit to China as a great success.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto made the remark during a meeting at his official
residence in Tokyo with U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright, who arrived here Friday night from Hong Kong to brief
Japan on Clinton's visit to China.
</P>
<P>
The bulk of their 25-minute meeting was spent discussing
Clinton's China visit, Japanese government officials said.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto told Albright that he had been following closely
Clinton's China tour and called the results a "great success,"
the officials said.
</P>
<P>
Albright also hailed the agreements reached between Washington
and Beijing, such as the mutual de-targeting agreement of
strategic nuclear weapons and the pledge on security and
nonproliferation cooperation on the arms race in South Asia.
</P>
<P>
Albright later held talks with Japanese Foreign Minister Keizo
Obuchi.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto and Obuchi "agreed that the improvement in the
U.S.-China relations is very much in Japan's interest as well. In
fact, it is a win-win-win outcome for the people in the United
States, Japan and China," Albright told a joint press conference
held with Obuchi.
</P>
<P>
"Relations between and among our three nations are not a
zero-sum game," she said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to Japan's financial system reform efforts, Albright
said: "I told Hashimoto that the United States was encouraged by
the plans that Japan announced on July 2 the reform of the banking
sector.
</P>
<P>
"As the president indicated yesterday, we now look forward to
Japan's taking swift, concerted action to implement these
measures," the state secretary said.
</P>
<P>
"I also emphasized the importance that the United States
attaches to Japanese economic recovery, which is critical not just
for this nation and its people, but for Asia and the world,"
Albright added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
