<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Crime Situation Stable Since Handover </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 4 (Xinhua) -- The overall crime situation in
Hong Kong has remained largely stable and fewer offenses have been
reported in the 12 months following Hong Kong's return to China on
July 1, 1997, a high-ranking police officer said on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Compared with the 12 months before the handover, the total
number of crimes recorded in the post-handover 12 months dropped
by 7.6 percent to 66,908 cases, with violent crimes falling by 4.4
percent, Senior Assistant Commissioner of Police Lau Yuk-kuen
said.
</P>
<P>
"Members of the public can be assured that Hong Kong continues
to be one of the safest and most stable cities in the world while
Hong Kong's stability relies very much on good law and order," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Lau reiterated that Hong Kong's connections with overseas law
enforcement agencies have stayed after the handover. 
</P>
</TEXT>
