<DOCNO> XIE19980704.0095 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korea to Increase Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, July 4 (Xinhua) -- The South Korean government and
business conglomerates Saturday agreed to increase the country's
exports to overcome the current financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
The nine-point agreement was published after South Korean
President Kim Dae-jung met tycoons of the groupings on Saturday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the government will complete the
restructuring of the ailing financial sector as soon as possible
to stabilize the nation's financial system, while the business
groups will work hard to restructure their operations and
management to survive the market system.
</P>
<P>
The conglomerates will be allowed to conduct the exchange of
businesses among themselves, and the government will offer
administrative support for the exchanges, said the agreement.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the government will provide 500 billion won (about
400 million U.S. dollars) in the second half of this year as a
credit guarantee fund for small-and medium-sized companies
specializing in export industries.
</P>
<P>
South Korea has been fighting against a financial crisis caused
by corporate failures and bad loans by financial institutions
since late last year.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement reached with the International Monetary Fund
(IMF) for a rescue loan of 57 billion U.S. dollars last December,
South Korea has to restructure its economy and open its markets
this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
