<HEADLINE> Jiang Confident in Development of Sino-Kazak Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA-ATA, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Chinese President Jiang
Zemin said here Saturday that his visit to Kazakstan is
"fruitful," expressing confidence in the bright future of the
development of Sino-Kazak relations.
</P>
<P>
The complementary agreement on border issues between the two
countries marked a complete resolution of their remaining border
issues, added Jiang at a press conference after its signing
ceremony.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, the second of its kind, will greatly contribute
to the regional stability, said the Chinese president.
</P>
<P>
China and Kazakstan signed a border agreement in April, 1994
and their first complementary border agreement during Jiang's
official visit to Kazakstan in July, 1996.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of the recent nuclear tests by India and Pakistan,
Jiang said China always stands for comprehensive ban and complete
destruction of nuclear weapons and opposes their proliferation in
any form.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the current tension in South Asia was
triggered by India single-handedly, saying any attempt to seek
hegemony or the big power status will fail under the present
international situation.
</P>
<P>
"China, as a close neighbor of South Asia, wishes peace and
stability for the region. We appeal to India and Pakistan to sign
the Treaty on the Non-Proliferation of Nuclear Weapons and the
Comprehensive Nuclear Test Ban Treaty unconditionally," said Jiang.
</P>
<P>
Also at the press conference, Kazak President Nursultan A.
Nazarbayev described the signing of the agreement as a significant
historical event.
</P>
<P>
Kazakstan regards China as a strategic partner oriented toward
the 21st century and its relations with China will further
develop, said Nazarbayev.
</P>
<P>
Jiang arrived here Friday to attend the five-nation meeting of
China, Kazakstan, Kyrgyzstan, Russia and Tajikistan, and pay a
one-day working visit to Kazakstan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
