<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Promises to Secure Oil Supply to Jordan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Iraq said Saturday that it will
continue the Iraqi-Jordanian agreement on oil cooperation to
secure the oil supply to Jordan for the second half of this year.
</P>
<P>
This came after Iraqi Oil Minister Amir Mohammed Rashid held a
meeting with visiting Jordanian Minister of Energy and Mineral
Resources Mohammed Saleh Hourani.
</P>
<P>
In a joint news conference after their meeting, Rashid said
President Saddam Hussein has ordered to guarantee supply of crude
and oil products to Jordan at preferential prices, despite Iraq's
difficulties in oil production for lack of spare parts.
</P>
<P>
Rashid said the U.N. Sanctions Committee has so far approved
none of the 40 contracts Iraq has had with foreign companies to
import spare parts for its dilapidated oil industry.
</P>
<P>
Iraq and Jordan signed the agreement on oil cooperation in
December last year, under which Jordan can get 4.8 million tonnes
of Iraqi crude and oil products per year at preferential prices.
</P>
<P>
At the press conference, Jordanian energy minister Hourani, who
arrived here Thursday leading an oil delegation, spoke highly of
the bilateral cooperation in oil sector, which he said is "running
smoothly" in the first half of this year.
</P>
<P>
Hourani said he will also discuss with Iraqi officials the
laying a 750-Kilometer pipeline, with a daily transport capacity
of 150,000 barrels, to carry Iraqi oil to Jordan's Zarqa refinery,
some 30 kilometers north of capital Amman. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
