<P>
LAGOS, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Rear Admiral Okhai Mike Akhigbe has
become Nigeria's No. 2 person as he was named the new chief of
general staff Friday night.
</P>
<P>
Akhigbe, chief of naval staff until his appointment, succeeded
Oladipo Diya, who vacated the office on December 20, 1997 following
his involvement in a coup plot and was sentenced to death by
a special military tribunal two months ago.
</P>
<P>
With the new position, Akhigbe will coordinate the affairs of
all the states of the federation in line with the policies of the
federal government.
</P>
<P>
His appointment is seen as capable of reducing the burden on
the office of the Head of State, General Abdulsalam Abubakar, who
took over the schedule following Diya's removal.
</P>
<P>
General Abubakar, the former chief of defense staff, became
the head of state on June 9, the second day after the sudden
death of his predecessor, late General Sani Abacha.
</P>
<P>
Akhigbe was born on September 29, 1946 at Fugar, Etsako in
southern Edo State.
</P>
<P>
After his secondary school education in Afenmai Anglican
Grammar School, Igarra, from 1961 to 1965, Akhigbe proceeded to
the Nigerian Defense Academy in northern Kaduna State, where he
spent three years from 1967 to 1969.
</P>
<P>
The former naval chief attended several courses in India,
Italy, the Netherlands, Germany, France and Britain in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
He began his naval career in April 1970, when he was
commissioned and appointed first lieutenant of the Nigerian navy.
He became a lieutenant three years later.
</P>
<P>
Prior to his appointment as the military governor of Ondo
State in August 1986, he was a captain. In 1987, he was
transferred to Lagos, the then national capital, also as military
governor.
</P>
<P>
The officer got to the peak in his naval career in 1994 when
he was named chief of naval staff.
</P>
<P>
Akhigbe has four children -- two sons and two daughters.
</P>
<P>
In recent times, he has emerged a critical voice against
military incursion into politics and canvassed quick restoration
of civil rule.
</P>
<P>
"It is unfortunate that the military has stayed long in power
and people are taking advantage of it to personalize every
issue," he said in May when he blamed his own constituency for
its own woes.
</P>
<P>
"I hope we sort out our political problems, get democratized
and face our professional jobs."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
