<HEADLINE> Philippine Senate to Debate Agreement With U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Philippine Press Secretary Rodolfo
Reyes said here Saturday that President Joseph Estrada will allow
the Senate to conduct its own discussion on the proposed
Philippines-U.S. Visiting Forces Agreement (VFA).
</P>
<P>
"The president is leaving this to the Senate for extensive
discussion," Reyes said in response to published reports that
Washington had started wooing the senators for immediate
ratification of the agreement.
</P>
<P>
Estrada will listen to the debates in the Senate, Reyes said,
adding that Foreign Secretary Domingo Siazon is now preparing some
pointers on the issue.
</P>
<P>
Reyes said former senate president Edgardo Angara will be asked
to find out if the VFA is included in the legislative agenda of
the Estrada administration.
</P>
<P>
Angara was the vice presidential running-mate of President
Estrada during the May 11 elections.
</P>
<P>
According to reports, Senator Juan Flavier had been personally
approached by U.S. Ambassador Thomas Hubbard, who explained the
benefits of a VFA to the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed by the Ramos administration in
January, but needs Senate ratification. Under the agreement,
visiting U.S. soldiers would enjoy immunity if they commit any
crimes on the Philippine territory. 
</P>
</TEXT>
