<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Int'l Great Apes Conference Opens in Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 4 (Xinhua) -- The Third International
Conference on Great Apes of the World opened in Sarawak, East
Malaysia, Saturday to deliberate on how to conserve great apes
faced with extinction threats worldwide.
</P>
<P>
Over 60 researchers, conservationists and ape experts will
present findings from their wildlife research, conservation and
captive management for orangutans (a kind of ape) and other great
apes faced with extinction threats worldwide at the three-day
conference, according to reports reaching here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The conference themed "Securing Great Ape Survival into the
Next Millennium" is expected to come up with an action plan to
address the great apes' conservation, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
"Great apes and their habitat have been threatened and
exploited by humans during this century, yet their very survival
as free-living species is now in question as we enter the new
millennium," said Sarawak Development Institute (SDI), the
conference coordinator, in a statement earlier.
</P>
<P>
Sarawak, the largest state in Malaysia, was chosen to host the
conference because it is part of Borneo Island which is
world-famous for orangutans and many of them still inhabit
Sarawak's forests.
</P>
<P>
Currently there are an estimated 40,000 orangutans still
inhabiting Borneo and Sumatra. But 10 years ago, these two islands
had about 180,000 orangutans, according to Los Angeles-based
Orangutan Foundation International President Birute Galdikas at
the conference.
</P>
<P>
She said that on global conservation of the great apes, it was
important to save the forests in terms of biodiversity
conservation for which orangutans could be used as a monitor.
</P>
<P>
Opening the conference, Sarawak State Tourism Minister James
Masing said the recent prolonged drought in Borneo, the forest
fires and encroachment by man had destroyed much of the primates'
habitat and natural surrounding.
</P>
<P>
He said the Second Tourism Master Plan of the Sarawak State
recommended the proper management of national parks, wildlife
sanctuaries and nature reserves up to the year 2010 to protect its
wildlife, especially orangutans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980704.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
