<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh to Announce New Export Policy Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 4 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government will soon
announce the export policy 1997-2002, which stresses expansion of
the export base to reduce extreme dependence on limited items, The
Financial Express daily reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"If products are not diversified and new items are not included
in the list of exportables, the country's export would face severe
setback in the near future," says the new export policy already
approved by the Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
At present, the country's exports are dominated by items such
as ready-made garments, knitwear, leather and leather products,
frozen food and tea.
</P>
<P>
Only by developing exportables' production infrastructure, can
the country's export sector maintain its growth in line with the
projected seven percent GDP (gross domestic product) growth rate
during the fifth five-year plan period (1997-2002), the policy
points out.
</P>
<P>
The policy's major objectives include achieving the highest
growth rate through increasing exports to the regional and
international markets and reducing the gap between export earnings
and import payments.
</P>
<P>
It stresses concerted measures to enter the post-Uruguay Round
globalized market by increasing productivity of export items and
reducing their production costs and improving the quality.
</P>
<P>
The new export strategy aims at creating a trained manpower in
the sector and bringing high-tech facilities in the production
units.
</P>
<P>
It also emphasizes exploitation of the benefits given for the
least developed countries by the World Trade Organization and
measures to have raw materials for export industries at world
price.
</P>
<P>
The sectors to get special importance in the policy include
computer software, leather and leather goods, ready-made garments
and other prospective non-traditional items.
</P>
<P>
Devaluation of the country's currency, taka, already done by
the government several times, is also seen as a vital tool in the
policy to keep the country's products competitive in the
international market.
</P>
<P>
Other important steps to be taken for implementing the policy
include establishment of an export-import bank, setting up
information centers in various countries with network facilities
and establishing a trade and investment training institute and
reorganizing the Export Promotion Bureau, according to the policy.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980704.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
