<HEADLINE> Cesare Maldini Faces Possible Sack after Defeat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
PARIS, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Italian coach Cesare Maldini will
possibly be sacked after his team suffered a penalty shoot-out defeat
to hosts France in the quarter-finals at World Cup finals on Friday.
</P>
<P>
It is the third World Cup in a row that Italy has been sent
packing in the same way.
</P>
<P>
Italian Soccer Federation president Luciano Nizzola made no
effort to defend Maldini after the match:"It is premature to be
talked about now," said Nizzola, "I've nothing to reproach the team
for, but clearly, I am bitterly disappointed about the way things
have worked out."
</P>
<P>
Nizzola said:"This group of players has been crying about this
defeat. But I have to say that I think that's excessive--because I
don't think they have anything to feel guilty about."
</P>
<P>
Maldini said he felt his future was uncertain:"There will be a
time to think about the future, but this is not the right moment."
</P>
<P>
Paolo Maldini, captain of the Italian team and son of Cesare
Maldini, said he was not satisfied:"I've played 19 matches in World
Cup finals and lost only one. But I've never won anything."
</P>
<P>
"At the moment, the bitterness is so strong that I feel like
finishing with the national team and to making way for younger
players," Paolo Maldini said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
