<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Relocation of HK Airport From Kai Tak to Chek Lap Kok </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 4 (Xinhua) -- The process of relocation of the
Hong Kong International Airport from Kai Tak to Chek Lap Kok
started on May 6 to be consistent with new airport opening on July
6.
</P>
<P>
The unprecedented move comprises five phases over a
three-month period, of which the night move during the late hours
of July 5 and the early hours of July 6 is "most critical".
</P>
<P>
The objectives of the relocation are to achieve a seamless
transfer of airport operation from Kai Tak to Chek Lap Kok and to
ensure that Hong Kong, at all times, has a fully functional
airport whether at Kai Tak or Chek Lap Kok, according to the
Airport Authority tasked with building and managing the new
airport.
</P>
<P>
The dates and times of the various phases are as
follows: pre-advance move, from May 6 to June 4; advance move,
from June 5 to June 21; main body move, from June 22 to 17:30
hours July 5; night move, from 17:30 hours July 5 to 06:30 hours
July 6; and follow-on move till August 5.
</P>
<P>
The relocation exercise is planned on the basis of three
inter-linked operations: the departure from Kai Tak; the journey
from Kai Tak to the new airport, including allocation of time
slots for moves by road, sea and air; reception and distribution
at Chek Lap Kok.
</P>
<P>
The bulk of the movement of vehicles and equipment will take
place by road, but will be supplemented, especially in the final
stages, by barge transportation and in night move by air
transport.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that 10,000 land movements, 70 barge movements
and 30 aircraft movements will be required through the exercise,
according to the Airport Authority.
</P>
<P>
The success of the move requires close coordination between the
 Airport Authority, various government departments such as Police,
 Transport Department and Marine Department, and all business
partners.
</P>
<P>
Contingency planning in case of bad weather has been prepared
as early July is prone to typhoon and rainstorm.
</P>
<P>
Postponement of the final stages of the move will be considered
 if there is any likelihood of winds high enough, for example, 40
kilometers per hour or above, to necessitate partial closure of
the Lantau Link, a major road link between Kowloon and the new
airport.
</P>
<P>
The hoisting of a No. 3 typhoon signal will also mean the
automatic suspension of the sea move as barge operators' insurance
is no longer valid under the conditions.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
