<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-04 08:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Asks U.S. to Do More in Anti-Drug Campaign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Iran's prosecutor-general has said
the United States can play a more effective role in fighting drugs
if it has good will toward Iran's anti-drug campaign.
</P>
<P>
Morteza Moghtadai was responding to Washington's claimed
support to Iran's efforts to crack down on the rampant drug
traffic through its territory.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the moderate daily Iran News, Moghtadai
blamed the U.S. for adopting "a political approach toward efforts
to combat illicit drug trafficking and abstains from voicing the
truth."
</P>
<P>
It was only lately that the U.S. acknowledged Iran's anti-drug
efforts, after both began to seek ways to ease their long-running
hostility. U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright last month
praised Iran's fight against drugs, saying Washington was ready to
improve ties with Tehran.
</P>
<P>
However, the Iranian official accused some Americans of
"supporting drug traffickers." "We have documents proving that the
Americans themselves escalate addiction, and distribute and
produce narcotics," Moghtadai said.
</P>
<P>
He claimed that Mafia groups and professional smugglers that
distribute and bring heroin into Iran are supported by their
American collaborators.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday Iran threw 50 tonnes of opium and one tonne of
heroin into fire on the occasion of the World Anti-Drug Day, to
exhibit its determination and call on the international community
to help its campaign. 
</P>
</TEXT>
