<HEADLINE> Zambian Police Probe Plot to Murder UNIP Leaders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 4 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian police are
investigating a plot to eliminate five central committee members
of the country's largest opposition United National Independence
Party (UNIP) as wrangles in the embattled political party
continue.
</P>
<P>
Three Zambians and three South Africans who have been
allegedly hired to assassinate the UNIP leaders have been named
and the three Zambians are former military personnel,
the government-owned Zambia Daily Mail reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Police service spokesman Beenwell Chimfwembe confirmed here
Friday receipt of the plan reported to police by some of the
people who have been listed for elimination.
</P>
<P>
Those to be eliminated include party secretary general
Sebastian Zulu, party chairman Malimba Masheke, publicity deputy
chairman Pickson Chitambala, deputy party secretary general
Fenwick Chifunda and chairman for youth Mwashikanda Liso,
according to the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The paper said that Liso confirmed that he had reported the
matter to police after sympathizers informed him about the plot.
</P>
<P>
The person leading the plot has also been named while the
hit-men have been put under a 24-hour police surveillance.
</P>
<P>
Liso said the three South Africans had been accommodated
within Lusaka and dates when the scheme is to be carried out have
been identified.
</P>
<P>
In a note shown to the paper by Liso, the plot is to start on
July 5 with Zulu and Chifunda as the targets. The rest are to be
attacked on August 4 with a possibility of change of plans if the
initial days planned for the attack are not suitable for various
reasons.
</P>
<P>
UNIP led by former president Kenneth Kaunda has been entangled
in the past months in internal wrangles over party leadership
while Kaunda was detained for allegedly involvement in the
country's foiled military coup.
</P>
<P>
The party is scheduled to hold a crucial central committee
meeting Saturday at which several matters are to be tabled
including the impending resignation of party president Kaunda.
</P>
</TEXT>
