<BODY>
<HEADLINE> A Brief History of Hong Kong's Kai Tak Airport </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Kai Tak, formally named Hong Kong
 International Airport, has emerged as one of the world's busiest
airports in tandem with the growth of the city it has served for
more than 70 years.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, its last full year of operation, Kai Tak, handled 28.3
 million passengers and 1.79 million tons of cargo, ranking the
third among global airports in terms of international passengers
and topping the rank in terms of cargo throughput.
</P>
<P>
Total aircraft movements hit 165,154 in 1997, making Kai Tak
one of the busiest airports in the world -- and all on a single
runway. To put in another way, every two minutes during peak hours
there is an aircraft taking off or landing at Kai Tak.
</P>
<P>
More than 60 airlines now offer direct regular services to link
Hong Kong with more than 100 destinations all over the world.
</P>
<P>
Kai Tak is so important that it handles, in value terms, one
quarter of Hong Kong's total imports of goods, one third of
exports, and one sixth of re-exports.
</P>
<P>
Built on a reclaimed field of 334 hectares, Kai Tak is
characterized by a 3,390-meter runway protruding from northwest to
southeast into the Kowloon Bay.
</P>
<P>
At the very beginning, the piece of land was reclaimed for a
residential housing scheme by two businessmen, Ho Kai and Au Tak,
after whom the airport was named. The company they formed,
unfortunately, went bust soon, and the reclaimed land was left
vacant until it was found suitable to be used as an airfield.
</P>
<P>
The first recorded flight from Kai Tak took place on Lunar New
Year's Day in 1925. Hong Kong's aviation began on this unique
piece of land with a flying school and a British military flying
unit. The first commercial flight landed on March 23, 1936 from
Penang with one passenger and 16 bags of mail, signifying the
advent of true commercial aviation at Kai Tak.
</P>
<P>
Entering into the 1950s, Kai Tak embarked on an era of rapid
development of airport facilities in order to catch up with the
phenomenal growth of passenger volume, which frequently recorded
an increase of 20 percent per year.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, Kai Tak reached an important milestone as it became
the third busiest in the world in terms of international
passengers and the busiest in terms of cargo throughput. The
airport handled a historic high of 29.5 million international
passengers, and 1.56 million tons of cargoes that year.
</P>
<P>
Cramped in residential blocks near the Kowloon Bay, Kai Tak has
no room for expansion both in space and time. Instead of running
around the clock, the airport handles no flight movements, both
takeoffs and landings, between 11:30 p.m. and 6:30 a.m. out of
consideration for the 380,000 people living under the flight path.
</P>
<P>
Kai Tak will be closed on July 6, 1998 when a new airport at
Chek Lap Kok is opened for business. According to the Planning,
Environment and lands Department, Kai Tak will be redeveloped to
house Hong Kong residents and a feasibility study is underway.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
