<HEADLINE> Trade Pact Between Kenya, Zimbabwe Urged to Be </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 4 (Xinhua) -- A Kenyan cabinet minister has
urged the 14-year-old trade agreement between Kenya and Zimbabwe
be reviewed to reflect the changes that have taken place in
southern and eastern Africa.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan Trade Minister Joseph Kamotho cited developments within
the Common Market for Southern and Eastern Africa (COMESA) and
the emergence of South Africa as a powerful trading nation after
the end of apartheid.
</P>
<P>
It was regrettable that there is a low volume of trade between
the two states and that the around four-billion-Shilling (67.34
million U.S. Dollars) commerce was heavily in favor of Zimbabwe,
he was quoted Saturday by the Daily Nation newspaper as saying.
</P>
<P>
Kenya exported goods worth some 520 million Shillings (8.75
million Dollars) to Zimbabwe and imported goods worth about 3.3
billion Shillings (55.6 million Dollars) from it last year.
</P>
<P>
Most of the Kenyan imports from Zimbabwe are raw materials for
the manufacture of iron and steel products, the minister said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Kamotho emphasized the need for businessmen from both
countries to attend regional trade fairs, saying Kenyan traders
got orders worth 100 million Shillings (1.68 million Dollars)
last year at the Harare International Trade Fair.
</P>
<P>
He also revealed that Kenya is working on modalities for the
establishment of a trade agreement with South Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
