<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ningxia Protects Islamic Venues (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YINCHUAN, July 4 (Xinhua) -- The city of Wuzhong, in northwest
China's Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region, revised a plan not a long
ago to widen its West Ring Road in order to protect an Islamic
Mosque which would have otherwise been destroyed.
</P>
<P>
A detour moved the road 10 meters away the originally planned
route, with change in construction costing well over one million
yuan (120,000 US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Ningxia, China's only provincial-level autonomous region
inhabited by the people of ethnic Hui group, has extended great
efforts over the past 20 years to protect religious sites in
strict accordance with state policies on nationalities and
religion.
</P>
<P>
The number of Islamic venues has grown from 1,800 when the
region was founded some 40 years ago to more than 3,000 sites,
according to Zhang Zhongxiao, an official with the Ningxia
Religious Affairs Bureau.
</P>
<P>
Each mosque in the region serves an average of 500 Muslims, or
a figure well above the national average of one mosque for every
1,000 Muslims, said Zhang, adding that China has more than 20
million Muslims with some 23,000 mosques.
</P>
<P>
Since the beginning of 1980s, Ningxia opened all related
projects for religious activities in the 1980s and since
refurbished numerous mosques with financial assistance from both
the central and local governments, with the former allocating well
over two million yuan (241,000 US dollars) for relevant projects.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980704.0160 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-04 06:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 1stlead: New Quake Hits Turkey, Over 400 Injured </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 4 (Xinhua) -- More than 400 people were injured in
a new earthquake that hit southern Turkey early Saturday, the
semi-official Anatolia News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The agency said that the earthquake, measuring 5.1 degrees on
the open-ended Richter scale, took place at 05:15 local time (0215
GMT) and its epicenter was at the city of Adana, some 400
kilometers southeast of the capital.
</P>
<P>
The agency said that some people got injured by jumping from
their balconies and some people suffered heart attack due to
panic. This is the the strongest of more than 70 aftershocks after
the previous earthquake a week ago, which ravaged the city, killed
more than 140 people and injured about 1,500 others.
</P>
<P>
It added that the injured were rushed to various hospitals in
Adana for treatment.
</P>
<P>
Last Saturday, Adana and its nearby city of Ceyhan in southern
Turkey were jolted by a strong earthquake measuring 6.3 degrees on
the Richter scale. 
</P>
</TEXT>
