<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ningxia Protects Islamic Religious Venues (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The autonomous region has placed the Tongxin Mosque in Tongxin
County, a famous religious site with a history of more than 600
years, under special protection, and the regional government has
allocated 770,000 yuan (928,000 US dollars) on three separate
occasions for repairs and maintenance activities.
</P>
<P>
The regional government also closed a factory which occupied a
mosque in the city of Yinchuan and allocated over 500,000 yuan
(60,000 US dollars) for repairs.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Chinese government promulgated a set of
regulations for administering sites for religious activities in
1994, with regional authorities also adopting corresponding
measures to safeguard the legitimate rights and interests of
related sites.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Zhang said, governments at all levels in the region
have adopted impartial policies for approving and registering all
religions and religious venues.
</P>
<P>
Ningxia, one of the country's five autonomous regions with
regional autonomy for national minorities, has a population of 5.3
million people, including 1.78 million members of the ethnic Hui
group, or approximately one third of the local population.
</P>
<P>
When asked on China's religious policies, Li Zemin, a
69-year-old Imam of Tongxin Mosque, said with joy: "the government
protects mosques and does not interfere with normal religious
activities and we can go to mosque and attend service daily."
</P>
</TEXT>
