<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton's Visit to China a Success: HK Newspaper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 4 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton's
just-concluded visit to China was very successful and it has
brought the Sino-U.S. relations to a new stage of cooperation, an
editorial of Hong Kong's Chinese-language newspaper Wen Wei Po
said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. president finished his nine-day visit on Friday, when
his special plane left Hong Kong, the last leg of his China trip,
for home.
</P>
<P>
The change in President Clinton's policies toward China and a
switch from confrontation to cooperation for a constructive
strategic partnership with China fully accords with the interests
of the United States, the editorial said. Clinton's visit to China
has accomplished what had been expected and was a complete
success, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The agreement reached by the heads of state of the two
countries not to point their strategic nuclear weapons at each
other demonstrates to the world that China and the United States
are partners, not adversaries, as pointed out by President Jiang.
The two countries can trust and cooperate with each other, the
newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The two countries decided to push forward their bilateral
relations to increase cooperation in more fields in the
future. The improvement of Sino-American relations is consistent
with the current trend of peace and development. In such
historical circumstances, the two countries have more things in
common and the foundation for cooperation has been further
strengthened, the editorial continued.
</P>
<P>
The Taiwan issue is among the most important and sensitive ones
in Sino-U.S. relations. In his meeting with Chinese President
Jiang Zemin in Beijing, President Clinton publicly reiterated that
the United States upholds the one-China policy and abides by the
principles contained in the three Sino-U.S. joint communiques, and
does not support Taiwan's independence, nor "one China, one
Taiwan," nor "two Chinas," nor Taiwan's bid to join any
international organizations made of only sovereign states.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. president reaffirmed this policy later in Shanghai and
he expressed during the visit to Hong Kong his support for
dialogue across the Taiwan Straits and settlement of disputes
through peaceful means. These statements will play a positive role
in promoting Sino-American relations, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
There are differences between China and the United States, but
they can be discussed through open and honest discussions.
</P>
<P>
The United States should treasure the favorable trend in the
development of the Sino-American relations, keep its promise and
take resolute actions to overcome obstacles to the improvement of
the bilateral relations, the editorial added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
