<DOCNO> XIE19980704.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interview: Great Airport, Big Challenge to Builder  (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Building the Hong Kong new
airport is the biggest challenge for Dr. Henry Townsend in his
30-year career managing civil engineering and infrastructure
projects worldwide.
</P>
<P>
"I would say this is probably the most challenging job I've
ever faced in my career," said Townsend, who has been Chief
Executive Officer of the Hong Kong Airport Authority (AA) for six
years, overseeing the day-to-day progress of the mammoth project
that took eight years to finish.
</P>
<P>
The new airport is built on a reclaimed field named Chek Lap
Kok off the northern coast of Lantau Island, 25 km to the west of
the Hong Kong central business district.
</P>
<P>
It took two years and a half to complete the reclamation and
excavation to create the 1,248-hectare airport platform. "It is
the largest undertaking of this kind in the world," said Townsend,
who is a registered professional engineer from the United States,
but has built up his presence in Hong Kong for almost a decade.
</P>
<P>
Before the completion of the platform, construction of the
nine-level Y-shaped passenger terminal building had started.
Covering a total floor space of 516,000 square meters at opening,
this is the world's largest airport terminal, which stretches 1.27
km from its entrance to the end of the Y-shaped concourse.
</P>
<P>
"It was a fast-track type of construction project of enormous
magnitude, and required a considerable amount of coordination with
and between the contractors that were involved," said the
65-year-old engineer.
</P>
<P>
Asked what made it a success to complete such a massive project
on time and within budget, Townsend spoke highly of the teamwork
spirit: "I think this is attributed to the people factor."
</P>
<P>
"One of the keys to the success of the airport building is to
orchestrate all of those various activities and have them finished
on time at the end in a successful way," he said.
</P>
<P>
The achievements, one coming after another, have brought to the
Chief Executive Officer and his colleague a great deal of
satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the new airport, as it opens, will probably
be the most advanced facility in the world considering the wide
use of the latest proven technology, in communications, ticketing,
baggage handling, and flight information screening.
</P>
<P>
Despite the complexity of construction, the airport is simple
and user-friendly. Townsend said that the flows of passengers
would be quite straight forward.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980704.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interview: Great Airport, Big Challenge to Builder (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
On arrivals, it is all a continuous one-level process on level
5. Passengers come through the concourses into immigration control
desks, baggage reclaiming area, customs inspection counters, the
meeting point, and finally to the transport center in a total
air-conditioned environment with good lighting and nice
surroundings.
</P>
<P>
On departures, there is only one-level change. Passengers come
in level 8, then go through the ramp, check-in area, immigration,
customs, and move one level down to the loading bridges.
</P>
<P>
In tandem with the opening of the new airport, an integrated
transport network will be started to link Chek Lap Kok to
different parts of Hong Kong with railway, bus, taxi and ferry
services.
</P>
<P>
Townsend looks on the new airport as a real opportunity for
Hong Kong. "Kai Tak has reached its maximum potential. The new
Chek Lap Kok removes growth constrains and allows a more orderly
development of aviation-related services for Hong Kong and the
surrounding region," he said.
</P>
<P>
The new airport is built to cater for aviation needs into the
next century, which is able to handle 35 million passengers and
three million tons of cargo a year at opening. Ultimately, it is
capable of handling 87 million passengers and nine million tons of
cargo annually.
</P>
<P>
As the new airport is to open for commercial operation in less
than 48 hours, Townsend said: "It takes a long and hard road up to
this point."
</P>
<P>
"Besides the pride being involved in the project, there will be
an immense relief to see it finished and operating successfully,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
But at the moment, he and all the AA staff members are busy
with preparations for the overnight move of airport operations
from Kai Tak to Chek Lap Kok on July 5, which will involve more
than 1,000 movements by air, sea and land.
</P>
<P>
"So far, I am optimistic that there should not be any major
problems," said Townsend, who will stay up all night at his office
at Chek Lap Kok to keep an eye on the transfer.
</P>
<P>
He said: "The fundamental point is that Kai Tak has to be 100
percent safety and security right up to its final closure. And
similarly, the Chek Lap Kok must be 100 percent safety and
security for the opening of commercial aviation on the morning of
July 6."
</P>
<P>
Townsend will continue to oversee the initial stage of
management of the new airport until November 1998 when his term of
appointment expires. He has not worked out a plan for the future
yet, but the gray-haired engineer laughed: "Certainly, running a
project of this size at my age is not (within the plan)."
</P>
<P>
"Look back on it, I should say what a wonderful opportunity it
has been to work in Hong Kong," he said. "The project is extremely
challenging, and certainly for that reason, it has been most
rewarding in terms of professional satisfaction." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
