<DOCNO> XIE19980704.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNDP Undertakes Training Project in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 4 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Development Program (UNDP)
has undertaken a massive program to train elected representatives
of the lowest-level local governments of union councils and
municipalities in Bangladesh, The Independent daily reported
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
A total of 60,000 people's representatives, including chairmen
and members of union councils and chairmen and commissioners of
municipalities, will be trained under the project titled "Building
Capacity for Local Governance."
</P>
<P>
The UNDP will provide about 490 million taka (some 10.6 million
U.S. dollars) for the five-year project with the National
Institute of Local Government as the executive agency and the
project is scheduled to be completed in 2002.
</P>
<P>
The project is aimed at producing well-trained, well-oriented
local representatives equipped with skills and knowledge to serve
their constituents effectively and in turn this will help develop
a more responsive and transparent system of local governance, a
UNDP document on the matter was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The key aim of the training program will be to institutionalize
the participatory process of governance at the local level between
the chairperson and the legislative body, as well as between local
government bodies and female and male constituents, the document
stated.
</P>
<P>
The ultimate beneficiaries of the project will be the
electorate, whose relationship to processes of local governance
will be greatly enhanced by the effective training of their
elected representatives, it said.
</P>
<P>
After being trained, the representatives will be more
accountable and responsive, with greater sensitization and
capacity to deliver services justly, equitably and responsively,
the document added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
