<HEADLINE> Philippine Govt to Allocate More Funds to Farm Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 4 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government is making
available 100 million pesos (25 million U.S. dollars) of credit to
local farmers, in a bid to boost the agriculture sector.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine News Agency reported Saturday that the amount
was sourced from the Development Bank of the Philippines to
implement a Crops Development Financing Program, which is designed
to enhance the productivity and income of farmers.
</P>
<P>
The program covers areas identified by the Department of
Agriculture to be suitable to viable, long-gestating crops with
Cotabato, Zamboanga, Agusan, Misamis, Davao, Sarangani and Basilan
as priority provinces, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
It said that eligible borrowers are individuals, partnerships
and corporations registered with the Securities and Exchange
Commission with majority Filipino capital.
</P>
<P>
Philippine President Joseph Estrada, who succeeded Fidel Ramos
Tuesday, has vowed to boost the farm sector in his six-year term
in order to narrow the gap between the country's rich and the
poor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
