<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Costa Rica to Improve Coffee Quality </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, July 3 (Xinhua) -- President of the Costa Rican
Coffee Institute (ICAFE) Arnoldo Lopez proposed to develop a
program to improve the quality of coffee before a possible price
drop in the international market.
</P>
<P>
The price of a quintal (46 kilos) of coffee dropped from 177.10
U.S. dollars quoted in January to 110.75 dollars Thursday in the
New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the speculators action in the stock market, the news
of abundant harvests in some producing countries contributed to
the drop, Lopez said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"The prospect is disappointing, because the price is getting
closer to 100 dollars per quintal," said Lopez.
</P>
<P>
The price for a quintal was above 150 dollars in the last three
years, which, among other reasons, caused the implementation of a
quota system by the bigger producing countries to prevent an
excessive increase of the supply.
</P>
<P>
Facing a foreseeable period of low price, the new ICAFE
president announced a program to introduce high technology in
production to improve the quality of coffee and the productivity.
</P>
<P>
Coffee, which for years has been the major export of Costa
Rica, continues to be an important element for the country's trade
balance and the sustenance for thousands of small and medium
producers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
