<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh to Construct Another Huge Bridge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh will start building the
country's second largest bridge, Paksey Bridge, late this year,
English newspapers here reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The 2.15-kilometer-long and 18.1-meter-wide bridge will be
constructed over the Padma River, which runs from northwest to
southeast Bangladesh, at a total cost of 5.96 billion taka (about
130 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Of the total amount, 100 million dollars will be provided by
the Japanese government under an accord signed between the two
sides and the rest will come from internal resources.
</P>
<P>
The foundations of the bridge, linking the country's northern
and southern parts which are separated by the mighty Padma River,
are expected to be laid in December this year and the whole
project would be completed by June 2001, the reports quoted
Communications Ministry sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
Feasibility study on the construction of the bridge was
conducted by two British and one local firms between March and
July 1996, the sources added.
</P>
<P>
Situated in South Asia and on the verge of the Bay of Bengal,
Bangladesh is crisscrossed by more than 230 rivers.
</P>
<P>
The transportation issue has constricted the country's economic
development. The Bangladeshi government has attached great
importance to bridge construction for rapid expansion of the
national economy.
</P>
<P>
The 4.8-kilometer-long and 18.5-meter-wide Jamuna Multipurpose
Bridge, the longest bridge in Bangladesh and in South Asia, was
completed with 950 million dollars and inaugurated on June 23 this
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
