<HEADLINE> Japanese PM Calls Clinton's China Visit Great Success </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto said here Saturday that U.S. President Bill Clinton's
just-concluded state visit to China is a great success.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto made the remark during a meeting at his official
residence in Tokyo with U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright, who arrived here Friday night from Hong Kong to brief
Japan on Clinton's visit to China.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto and Albright spent the bulk of their 25-minute
meeting discussing Clinton's China visit, Japanese government
officials said.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto told Albright that he had been following closely
Clinton's China visit and called the results as a "great success,"
the officials said.
</P>
<P>
Albright hailed accords reached during Clinton's China trip
between Washington and Beijing such as a mutual de-targeting
agreement of strategic nuclear weapons and a pledge on security
and nonproliferation cooperation on the arms race in South Asia.
</P>
<P>
On Japan's domestic issues, Albright told Hashimoto that the
U.S. government welcomed Japan's financial-system reform efforts
featured with a "bridge bank" scheme, referring to Clinton's
favorable remarks toward the plan at a press conference in Hong
Kong where the president ended his China trip Friday.
</P>
<P>
Ahead of his meeting with Clinton in Washington on July 22,
Hashimoto gave Albright an English translation of the Japanese
government's plan to salvage its bad loan-ridden banking system,
the officials said. 
</P>
