<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cambodian Landmine Casualties Decline in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, July 4 (Xinhua) -- The number of landmine
casualties in Cambodia dropped 50 percent from 1996 to 1,353 last
year, Cambodia Daily Saturday quoted a Cambodian Red Cross report
as saying.
</P>
<P>
The report based on a survey covering 90 percent of the
landmine affected areas in the country said the casualties totaled
2,766 in 1996, a record high since 1979 due to a large dry-season
offensive.
</P>
<P>
The survey also revealed a correlation between fighting and the
number of mine victims.
</P>
<P>
To illustrate, the report said that Kampot province, one of the
mine-ridden but stable areas, saw only 19 incidents last year
compared to 425 in Battambang province where fighting continued.
</P>
<P>
The decline in the number of victims indicates that people have
learned to co-exist with the mines, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Last year also saw a decline in deaths to 18 percent of the
victims from its long-term average of 36 percent from 1979 to 1996.
</P>
<P>
Military-related casualties were a slight majority of the
victims in 1997 at 52 percent, with 48 percent related to civilian
causes.
</P>
<P>
Women accounted for 10 percent of the total victims in 1997 as
previous years while men remained to be the majority.
</P>
<P>
Two decades of civil war and lingering unrest have turned
Cambodia into one of the most heavily mined countries in the
world. There are an estimated four to six million mines littered
in Cambodian soil and mine explosions have maimed and killed many
innocent people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980704.0183 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Autonomy Is Solution to Kosovo Crisis: Italian FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, July 3 (Xinhua) -- A "strong autonomy" for Kosovo's
ethnic Albanians is a solution to their conflicts with the Serb
government of Yugoslavia, Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini
said at a cabinet meeting on Friday.
</P>
<P>
"A status of a strong autonomy constitutes a solution to the
crisis and the international community will continue to exert
pressure on all sides in this direction," Dini said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the hypothesis of independence for the Serbian
province of Kosovo "does not represent a solution and must be
discouraged as it fuels further and wider conflicts."
</P>
<P>
Both the ethnic Albanian majority in Kosovo and Serb
authorities "must be strongly urged to swiftly cease armed clashes
and re-establish global and constructive dialogue in the prospect
of a peaceful and negotiated solution, based on realism and
Germany foresight," the Italian minister said.
</P>
<P>
According to the Beta news agency in Belgrade, leader of
Kosovo's Albanian majority Ibrahim Rugova on Friday rejected
autonomy for Kosovo, saying that the region must either be
independent or become an international protectorate.
</P>
<P>
He added that the future of Kosovo must be decided by the
population there.
</P>
<P>
U.S. envoy Richard Holbrooke arrived in Belgrade on Friday for
talks with Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic on Kosovo and is
expected to travel to Pristina on Saturday to meet Rugova, Beta
reported.
</P>
<P>
Russian Deputy Foreign Minister Nicolai Afanievski will also be
in Belgrade on Saturday and may hold meetings with Holbrooke to
coordinate, as they did last week, the diplomatic efforts of
Washington and Moscow to re-open dialogue between the Albanians in
Kosovo and Belgrade authorities.
</P>
<P>
In Warsaw, Austrian Foreign Minister Wolfgang Schuessel on
Friday urged greater cooperation between the European Union and
the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) to
"create a climate favorable to political negotiations on the
Kosovo crisis."
</P>
<P>
Poland currently holds the presidency of the OSCE and Austria
the European Union's rotating presidency.
</P>
<P>
Schuessel and his Polish counterpart Bronislaw Geremek agreed
after their talks on Friday to make a joint effort to support
moderate forces in Kosovo and to create a joint task force to
monitor the conflict. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
