<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Economic Measures Called Successful </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Thai Finance Minister Tarri
Nimmanahaeminda claimed on Friday that the government has
succeeded in implementing sound macroeconomic measures under the
International Monetary Fund's prescriptions one year after the
baht's devaluation.
</P>
<P>
The Thai government led by Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai has
successfully stabilized the baht's exchange rate and brought the
currency to an appropriate level, Tarrin said in remarks published
by The Nation newspaper Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the short-term interest rate could be lowered to
around 16 percent from its peak of 22 percent earlier this year,
Tarrin said.
</P>
<P>
"Interest rates could be brought down further if the current
stability in regional foreign exchange rates continues," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Tarrin's deputy, Pisit Lee-artham, echoed the view,
saying the government has been successful in bringing down the
baht from its peak of 56 baht against the U.S. dollar in January
to its recent levels of around 40 baht.
</P>
<P>
The former government of Chavalit Yongchaiyudh floated the baht
on July 2 last year and sought an IMF bailout package valued at
17.2 billion dollars in August. The devaluation of the baht
triggered a regional currency crisis that also struck Indonesia
and South Korea.
</P>
<P>
After the baht was floated, the Thai economy was hit hard by
the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Pisit said if the regional crisis had not happened, the baht's
floatation would have created a more successful situation.
</P>
<P>
Looking back to last year, the Chuan government has faced many
difficulties ranging from a depletion in official reserves to the
inheritance of a troubled banking sector and its severe damage to
the real economic sectors.
</P>
<P>
"It is not easy to solve all the problems in such a short
period of time," Tarrin said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the necessary solutions to ease the problems have
brought a great deal of pain to the country. The unemployment rate
is rising and so is the inflation rate which has hovered at about
10 percent in recent months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
