<HEADLINE> Thailand Considers Increasing Visa Application Fees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 4 (Xinhua) -- The Thai cabinet is considering
proposed amendments to the Immigration Law which will bring a
sharp rise in visa application and consular service fees.
</P>
<P>
The increase is necessary to bring the fees in line with
service costs, according to the Interior Ministry which proposed
the amendments.
</P>
<P>
A government official on Saturday confirmed press reports that
the proposal, already approved by the Foreign Ministry, will raise
the application fee for a single entry visa from 500 baht (12 U.S.
dollars) to 2,000 baht (48.7 dollars).
</P>
<P>
Under the proposal, a multiple entry visa valid for one year
will cost 5,000 baht (121 dollars).
</P>
<P>
The application fee for an immigrant's certificate is to jump
from 2,000 to 8,000 baht (195 dollars) and the certificate itself
is to cost 50,000 baht (1,219 dollars) instead of the present
200,000 (4,878 dollars).
</P>
<P>
However, the Interior Ministry said the fees, once raised,
could be lowered to reflect the actual costs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
