<HEADLINE> U.N. Urges Authorities to Facilitate Return of Refugees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZAGREB, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The Herzegovina-Neretva authorities
have not done enough to prevent the occurrence of many incidents
aimed at obstructing the return of refugees and exiled persons, a
report issued by the United Nations mission in Bosnia said Friday.
</P>
<P>
A total of 61 such incidents took place in that region between
March 26, when an agreement on the return of minority people was
signed, and June 30.
</P>
<P>
The mission reported that 64 Bosniak (Muslim) houses were
damaged, and ten Bosniak-owned vehicles were either destroyed or
damaged.
</P>
<P>
Though the regional authorities took certain measures to help
stabilize the situation, not a single person suspected of
participating in these incidents have been arrested, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, High International Representative for the
implementation of the Dayton Agreement in Bosnia-Herzegovina
Carlos Westendorp asked the authorities at various levels in
Bosnia to accelerate efforts to create conditions for a speedy
return of refugees to the country.
</P>
<P>
Westendorp warned that he would not hesitate to dismiss anyone
who obstructs the process of return and the establishment of
post-war ethnic balance. 
</P>
