<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shandong Province Increases Investment to Spur Economic Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, July 4 (Xinhua) -- East China's Shandong Province has
increased investment to spur economic growth since early this year.
</P>
<P>
Shandong invested a total of 22 billion yuan (2.65 billion US
dollars) in fixed assets in the first five months of this year, up
17 percent from the corresponding period of last year, according
to official statistics.
</P>
<P>
The funds have been invested mainly in construction of
infrastructure facilities, real-estate development and technical
renovations in enterprises, a provincial official said.
</P>
<P>
One of China's economic powerhouses, Shandong has set its
economic growth rate at 9 percent this year, 1 percent higher than
the national target.
</P>
<P>
"As our exports have been affected by the Asian financial
crisis, increasing investment has become a main way for us to
boost economic growth," the official said.
</P>
<P>
While investment in infrastructure has surged in recent months,
Shandong's banking system has also increased lending for housing
construction. The provincial branch of the Industrial and
Commercial Bank of China, the country's largest bank, issued more
than 50 million yuan (6 billion US dollars) in housing loans in
the January-May period.
</P>
<P>
The provincial branch of the China Construction Bank,
meanwhile, has decided to increase its yearly housing loan
portfolio by 310 million yuan (37 million US dollars) this year on
the basis of last year's 480 million yuan (58 million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Because of increased financial support, both Shandong's
investment and housing sales rocketed more than 60 percent in the
first five months.
</P>
<P>
Overall, Shandong's total investment this year is expected to
be 20 percent more than last year, the official said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980704.0192 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Guangdong Province Resolved to Tackle Unemployment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, July 4 (Xinhua) -- South China's booming Guangdong
Province, a showcase of the country's market reforms, will strive
to resolve the issue of re-employment of laid-off state-owned
enterprise workers within five years.
</P>
<P>
"We will keenly develop the service sector and increase job
training," Vice-Governor Zhong Qiquan said.
</P>
<P>
The first three years will be mainly devoted to ensuring a
basic living guarantee and re-employment for workers displaced by
state-owned industrial enterprises, especially those in sectors
such as coal, sugar refining and textiles, according to Zhong.
</P>
<P>
"The number of people re-employed must be greater than that of
newly displaced workers during the period," he said.
</P>
<P>
To these ends, Guangdong has decided to earmark 35 million yuan
to establish a provincial level re-employment fund in the period
from 1997 to 2000. The provincial capital of Guangzhou, and
Zhuhai, Shantou, Zhongshan and another four cities have set up
their own re-employment funds, valued at 95.7 million yuan in
aggregate.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong has also decided to set aside 50 million yuan in
special funds to help displaced workers who are exceptionally
needy.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics show that 534,000 workers were laid off in
Guangdong last year, with 289,000 finding new jobs the same year.
</P>
<P>
In the first five months of this year, 366,000 workers were
displaced in Guangdong while 132,000 were later re-employed.
</P>
<P>
Zhong said that Guangdong will take measures to ensure that no
less than 50 percent of the displaced workers will find new jobs
this year.
</P>
<P>
As China's market reforms go deeper, many workers have been
laid off by the state-owned enterprises, which were considered
overstaffed and inefficient.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980704.0193 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's MPR to Hold Meeting on November 10 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's People's Consultative
Assembly (MPR), the country's highest legal body, will hold an
extraordinary meeting on November 10 this year to set the date for
the next general election, MPR Chairman Harmoko announced.
</P>
<P>
Harmoko, who is also speaker of the House of Representatives
(DPR), said here Friday that the date was earlier than the
agreement he had struck with President B.J. Habibie, local leading
newspapers reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, an MPR meeting would be held by the end of
the year or beginning of 1999.
</P>
<P>
The MPR, which traditionally meets once every five years, met
in March to reelect President Soeharto for a seventh term in
office and Habibie for vice president. But Soeharto resigned in
May amid strong public pressure calling for political reforms.
</P>
<P>
Harmoko said the MPR leadership would assign the MPR Working
Committee to prepare the agenda and drafts to be discussed at the
extraordinary meeting.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that there would be some changes in the MPR
membership before the meeting.
</P>
<P>
President Habibie last week already appointed 41 members to
replace those who were personally selected by Soeharto.
</P>
<P>
The MPR includes the 425 MPs directly elected in parliamentary
elections and 75 president-appointed MPs from the armed forces,
plus a further 500 presidential appointees.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Harmoko said the general election will be held between
March and May next year and the MPR will elect a president and a
vice president at the end of 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
