<HEADLINE> Medical Graduates in Thailand to Face Unemployment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Prakrom Vuthipongse, permanent secretary of the Public Health
Ministry, was quoted as saying students due to graduate from 35
educational institutions next year will have to seek jobs
themselves, for the ministry does not have a budget to hire them.
</P>
<P>
"We will have to cancel the agreement made with the students
because we can't employ them," he said.
</P>
<P>
Under the ministry's scholarship schemes, all the students have
signed with the ministry agreements that they would be enrolled to
the civil service and work in hospitals under the ministry.
</P>
<P>
However, the number of staff at the ministry will be frozen for
up to two years under the Thai government's new policy.
</P>
<P>
Among students of 14 educational fields, nurses will be the
most affected, followed by analysts and sanitary experts. 
</P>
