<DOCNO> XIE19980704.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 40 Years of Recycling Remembered by the State </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Chinese leaders have long held that
collecting and recycling waste was an important part of saving
natural resources, reducing pollution and safeguarding the
ecology, said today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
The late premier Zhou Enlai made the case 40 years ago.
</P>
<P>
From 1953 through last year, China's major garbage collector
and recycler, the All-China Federation of Supply and Marketing
Co-operatives, gathered 350 million tons of various waste. But
this wasn't just garbage. The materials they recycled were worth
168 billion yuan (20.24 billion US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Those recycling efforts meant the saving of two billion tons of
minerals, 400 million tons of coal, 222 million cubic meters of
wood and the reduction of household and industrial waste.
</P>
<P>
Yesterday, during a news conference to mark the 40th
anniversary of the late Premier Zhou's inscription urging the
nation to recycle, officials looked back and tallied their success.
</P>
<P>
The wastes collected and recycled by Chinese co-operatives
amount to 63 percent of the country's total each year and about
800,000 people from the co-operatives circle are involved in
wastes collection, recycling and processing, marketing of recycled
materials research and education on saving wastes, according to
Zhang Yuqi, director of the Administration Office of Recycled
Materials under the federation.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that the collected waste covered more than
1,000 varieties, including iron and steel, nonferrous metals,
rubber, plastics and bones.
</P>
<P>
Widespread use of recycled materials has preserved natural and
energy resources in China, a developing country with one of the
lowest per capita mineral resources, he added.
</P>
<P>
Small private businesses will be encouraged to help expand
waste collection businesses and advanced technology will be
introduced to develop in-depth processing and comprehensive
utilization of waste materials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980704.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
