<HEADLINE> China Launches Major WB-Funded Energy-Saving Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 4 (Xinhua) -- China began to launch a large
energy conservation project in Beijing, Liaoning and Shandong
provinces with a World Bank (WB) loan of 63 million U.S. dollars
Friday.
</P>
<P>
According to today's China Daily, the project is also backed by
a 22-million-dollar donation from the Global Environmental Fund
(GEF) following successful pilot operations.
</P>
<P>
Zuo Liming, deputy director of the Energy Conservation and
Resource Utilization Department under the State Economic and Trade
Commission, said that the project will introduce efficient energy
conservation methods into China.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the bulk of the project will be carried out by
three model energy conservation companies established in Beijing,
northeast China's Liaoning Province and east China's Shandong
province.
</P>
<P>
These specialized energy management companies will provide a
series of proven energy conservation services, ranging from
project design, implementation, monitoring and management for
their customers, Zuo said.
</P>
<P>
On the basis of the three exemplary companies, China will
strive to spread this new mechanism to the whole country, and thus
stimulate the evolution of the energy conservation service
industry.
</P>
<P>
in addition, part of the GEF's donation will be used to support
the establishment of the State Energy Conservation Information
Distribution Center.  
</P>
</TEXT>
