<HEADLINE> Austria's Economy to Continue Strong Growth: Forecast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Austria's economy will carry its
strong momentum into next year despite negative influences from
Asia's financial crisis, two economic institutes said in their
forecasts released here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Austrian Institute for Economic Research (WIFO) predicted
that Austria's economy would grow by three percent this year and
3.2 percent in 1999.
</P>
<P>
The High-Level Institute (IHS) forecast a 3.1-percent rate for
the economic growth this year and a 2.8 percent for next year.
</P>
<P>
WIFO Director Helmut Kramer said good performances in exports
and industry as well as increasing investments in equipment were
boosting the country's economy and creating more jobs.
</P>
<P>
He predicted the number of jobless Austrians would go down next
year.
</P>
<P>
However, both institutes said Austria's economic growth would
slacken by 2000 at the latest.
</P>
<P>
The IHS even predicted that signs of weakening would appear as
early as next year.
</P>
<P>
IHS Director Bernhard Felderer said the economic crisis in some
Asian countries, especially in Japan, affected the United States
more than it did Europe and already led to a slowdown in the
U.S. economy.
</P>
<P>
The negative influences are also expected to spread to Europe,
at least in its exports to the U.S., he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
