<HEADLINE> Harbin Residents Consume More Meat, Eggs, Milk </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, July 4 (Xinhua) -- The per-capita consumption of meat,
eggs and milk in this capital of northernmost Heilongjiang
Province is among the highest of China's 36 major cities.
</P>
<P>
Official data indicates that residents of Harbin consume an
average 50.2 kilograms (kg) of meat, 30.5 kg of eggs and 43 kg of
milk each year. All three figures are higher than the officially
mandated index.
</P>
<P>
Harbin residents used to have insufficient consumption of meat,
eggs and milk, as the city's animal husbandry remained undeveloped
in past decades.
</P>
<P>
Because of the implementation of a national "vegetable basket"
project, Harbin's animal husbandry sector has grown significantly.
</P>
<P>
Currently, Harbin has more than 2,600 animal husbandry farms,
with 16 percent of the rural households engaged in raising
domestic animals.
</P>
<P>
Harbin has also set up a number of animal feed workshops and
animal product processing factories. The city's animal products
market has an annual sales volume of more than three billion yuan
(360 million U.S. dollars).  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
