<HEADLINE> Colombian Guerrillas Free 15 Female Hostages </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The Leftist guerrillas
Friday released 15 female hostages kidnapped in northeastern
Colombia three weeks ago, a presidential advisor said.
</P>
<P>
The girls, ranging from 13 to 21 years old, were handed over to
a humanitarian commission headed by Timorese Nobel Peace laureate
Jose Ramos Horta, some 300 kilometers north of the capital, said
Jose Noe Rios, the presidential peace commissioner.
</P>
<P>
The National Liberation Army (ELN), Colombia's second-largest
guerrilla group, said it kidnapped the girls because they belonged
to civic groups linked to the military. The hostages belonged to a
civic group called "Girl of Steel."
</P>
<P>
The freed hostages said they were treated well by their captors
but said they would quit the civic groups, fearing to be the
guerrillas' target again.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the ELN called the release as a "goodwill
gesture" following its announcement that it would hold peace talks
with President-elect Andres Pastrana after he takes office on
August 7. 
</P>
</TEXT>
