<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand to Discuss IRO Withdrawal With 2 Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Rubber producers Thailand, Malaysia
and Indonesia will meet in Phuket, southern Thailand, later this
month to discuss whether they should withdraw from the
International Rubber Organization (IRO), according to the Thai
Agriculture Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Companies from each country would also be invited to take part
in the July 23-25 meeting, Deputy Agriculture Minister Somchai
Sunthornwat was quoted Saturday by the newspaper The Bangkok Post
as saying.
</P>
<P>
The three countries control about three-quarters of the world's
rubber trade, which is 5 million tons annually.
</P>
<P>
Thailand claims that the organization has played an
insignificant role in shoring up the price of rubber.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, the Thai government has spent heavily to
support rubber prices. Last year, it spent 4.7 billion baht (114
million U.S. dollars) to buy 99,000 tons of rubber.
</P>
<P>
With the economic downturn forcing cuts in state spending,
Thailand is questioning the merits of paying 15 million baht
(365,000 dollars) a year for membership in the organization.
</P>
<P>
The International Rubber Organization groups 22 nations that
are major rubber producers and buyers. Thailand, the largest
producer, is expected to supply 1.8 million tons this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
