<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, July 4 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH -- Cambodia's National Election committee (NEC) has
launched a voter education campaign, aimed at informing voters
about procedures for casting a ballot on July 26, and for assuring
them that their votes will be secret.
</P>
<P>
About 50,000 copies of a first NEC leaflet giving general
information of the polls have been distributed nationwide with the
help of independent, non-government organizations.
(Cambodia-Election)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA -- Over 1,600 Somali refugees who sheltered at the
Hartishek Refugee Camp in eastern Ethiopia have been transported
to north Somalia.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia's Somali Region Refugee and Returnee Coordination
Office said in a report that the office, in collaboration with the
United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR), has managed
to repatriated 1,633 of the 6,000 Somali refugees voluntarily
registered to return to their country, the Ethiopian News Agency
reported Friday.  (Ethiopia-Somali Refugees)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ATHENS -- Greece criticized Friday the Western countries'
efforts for rapprochement with the Kosovo Liberation Army (KLA),
which is trying to win Kosovo's independence from Yugoslavia by
the use of force.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in the northern Greek city of Thessaloniki, Greek
Defense Minister Akis Tsohatzopoulos said that the Kosovo crisis
could not be solved through military means but in a political,
peaceful, diplomatic manner by granting the broadest possible
autonomy to Kosovo where ethnic Albanians make up 90 percent of
its nearly 2 million population. (Greece-Kosovo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russia will retain its strategic nuclear triad of
ground, sea and air forces until the year 2010, Russia's Security
Council announced Friday.
</P>
<P>
According to the Interfax news agency, the decision was taken
by the Security Council at a regular session chaired by President
Boris Yeltsin. (Russia-Nuclear Forces)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran Friday rejected the claim that Ahmad Rezaee, son
of former commander of the Islamic Revolutionary Guards Corps
(IRGC) Mohsen Rezaee seeking asylum in the United States, but
saying that he was kidnapped by Americans.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Iranian official news agency IRNA,
Ahmad's brother Ali Rezaee said that Ahmad was kidnapped by the
U.S. National Aeronautical and Space Administration (NASA)
"through a perfect plot initiated by an agent Majid Tawana one
year ago."  (Iran-US-Kidnapping) 
</P>
</TEXT>
