<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sampras, Ivanisevic Reach Wimbledon Men's Singles Final </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Defending Champion Pete Sampras of
the United States Friday cruised into the men's singles final of
the Wimbledon Tennis Championships after beating British favorite
Tim Henman.
</P>
<P>
World number one Sampras, who trounced all his opponents in
straight sets before reaching the semifinals, took the first set
by 6-3.
</P>
<P>
With the deafening home support at the Center Court, an
encouraged Henmen displayed top tennis and grabbed the second set
6-4.
</P>
<P>
Determined to win his fifth Wimbledon title this year, Sampras
launched aggressive attacks on the 23-year-old British player and
finally snatched the following two sets 7-5, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
In the other semifinal clash, Croatian veteran Goran Ivanisevic
took the first two sets 6-3, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
With only one point to losing the match, Dutch player Richard
Krajisek, the 1996 Wimbledon Champion, suddenly burst into life
and won the next two sets 7-5, 7-6.
</P>
<P>
In the crucial fifth set, Ivanisevic, who is well-known for his
hot temperament, displayed remarkable calmness and defended
brilliantly. After a long period of patient playing, Ivanisevic
finally hit the winner 15-13, striding into his third Wimbledon
final. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
