<HEADLINE> Mozambique Welcomes EU Lift of Ban on Fish </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Mozambican Prime Minister Pascoal
Mocumbi Friday expressed his satisfaction with the lifting of
European Union (EU) ban on importing fish from the east African
coastal countries including Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
The move is positive and the EU should do so earlier, Mocumbi
said at a press conference in Maputo.
</P>
<P>
The EU imposed ban on fresh fish imports from Mozambique,
Kenya, Uganda and Tanzania in the end of 1997 because its member
states were concerned over cholera in the sub-region.
</P>
<P>
According to the Mozambican News Agency, the World Food
Program (WFP) condemned the ban early this year, pointing out
that there had been no such cases as spreading of cholera through
imported food.
</P>
<P>
The EU disagreed with the WFP and has maintained the ban up to
six months.
</P>
<P>
The Mozambican government has for several times demanded that
the ban on fish import be lifted, noting that its fish products
have not polluted by cholera and asking the EU to come to
investigate.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the EU ban has caused Mozambican loss of
some six million U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
"We often hear the Europeans saying that Africa should open
its markets to them," Mocumbi said, adding that on contrary,
"Europe should open its markets to Africa earlier, because Africa
had opened its door to the Europeans when they first came to the
continent."
</P>
<P>
The Mozambican prime minister said he hopes that the EU would
better not make such irrational decision as the ban on fish
imports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
